{"title_page": "Clement Thornton Hallam", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = Sir Clement Thornton Hallam\n|image       = \n|caption     = \n|birth_date  = 4 January 1891\n|birth_place = [[Somerset East]], South Africa\n|death_date  = 17 March 1965 (aged 74)\n|death_place = [[Harrow on the Hill]]\n| education          = [[Bedford Modern School]] \n|other_names = \n|known_for   = Solicitor to the [[General Post Office]]\n|occupation  = \n|nationality = United Kingdom\n}}\n\n'''Sir Clement Thornton Hallam''' (4 January 1891 \u2013 17 March 1965) was solicitor to the [[General Post Office]].<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', March 19, 1965, p.17</ref><ref>''[[1939 England and Wales Register]]''</ref><ref>''Kelly\u2019s Handbook To The Titled, Landed and Official Classes, 1962'', Published by Kelly\u2019s Directories Limited 1962</ref>\n\n==Life==\nHallam was born in  [[Somerset East]], [[South Africa]] in 1891, the son of William Abner, from [[Leicester]], England, and Wilhelmina Charlotte, from South Africa.<ref>''1911 England Census''</ref>  He was educated at [[Bedford Modern School]].<ref>''Bedford Modern School of the Black And Red'', Andrew Underwood 1981</ref>\n\nIn 1914, Hallam was admitted to the bar<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1965|title=Obituary: Sir Clement Thornton Hallam|journal=The Solicitors' Journal|volume=109|page=260}}</ref> and he entered the Solicitor's Department of the [[General Post Office]] in 1915 becoming Solicitor to the [[General Post Office|GPO]] (1943\u201353).<ref name=\"WWW\">''Who Was Who'', Published by A&C Black Limited; online edition, Oxford University Press, 2014</ref>  During [[World War II]] he was seconded to the [[Royal College of Defence Studies|Imperial Defence College]].<ref name=\"WWW\"/>  He was made a [[Knight Bachelor]] in 1948.<ref name=\"WWW\"/>\n\nIn 1915, Hallam married Irene Parrington Faraday in [[Ormskirk]], [[Lancashire]].  They had two sons.  Sir Clement Hallam died in [[Harrow on the Hill|Harrow]] on 17 March 1965.<ref name=\"WWW\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hallam, Clement Thornton}}\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford Modern School]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the General Post Office]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n[[Category:South African emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = Sir Clement Thornton Hallam\n|image       = \n|caption     = \n|birth_date  = 4 January 1891<ref>''[[1939 England and Wales Register]]''</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Somerset East]], South Africa\n|death_date  = 17 March 1965 (aged 74)\n|death_place = [[Harrow on the Hill]]\n| education          = [[Bedford Modern School]] \n|other_names = \n|known_for   = Solicitor to the [[General Post Office]]\n|occupation  = \n|nationality = United Kingdom\n}}\n\n'''Sir Clement Thornton Hallam''' (4 January 1891 \u2013 17 March 1965) was solicitor to the [[General Post Office]].<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', March 19, 1965, p.17</ref><ref>''Kelly\u2019s Handbook To The Titled, Landed and Official Classes, 1962'', Published by Kelly\u2019s Directories Limited 1962</ref>\n\n==Life==\nHallam was born in  [[Somerset East]], [[South Africa]] in 1891, the son of William Abner, from [[Leicester]], England, and Wilhelmina Charlotte, from South Africa.<ref>''1911 England Census''</ref>  He was educated at [[Bedford Modern School]].<ref>''Bedford Modern School of the Black And Red'', Andrew Underwood 1981</ref>\n\nIn 1914, Hallam was admitted to the bar<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1965|title=Obituary: Sir Clement Thornton Hallam|journal=The Solicitors' Journal|volume=109|page=260}}</ref> and he entered the Solicitor's Department of the [[General Post Office]] in 1915 becoming Solicitor to the [[General Post Office|GPO]] (1943\u201353).<ref name=\"WWW\">''Who Was Who'', Published by A&C Black Limited; online edition, Oxford University Press, 2014</ref>  During [[World War II]] he was seconded to the [[Royal College of Defence Studies|Imperial Defence College]].<ref name=\"WWW\"/>  He was made a [[Knight Bachelor]] in 1948.<ref name=\"WWW\"/>\n\nIn 1915, Hallam married Irene Parrington Faraday in [[Ormskirk]], [[Lancashire]].  They had two sons.  Sir Clement Hallam died in [[Harrow on the Hill|Harrow]] on 17 March 1965.<ref name=\"WWW\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hallam, Clement Thornton}}\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford Modern School]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the General Post Office]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n[[Category:South African emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "AlexdeGrey", "label": "safe", "comment": "References", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clement_Thornton_Hallam"}
{"title_page": "Chlorophytum comosum", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|taxon = Chlorophytum comosum\n|image = Hierbabuena 0611 Revised.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Chlorophytum comosum'' 'Vittatum'\n|authority = ([[Carl Peter Thunberg|Thunb.]]) [[Henri Antoine Jacques|Jacques]]<ref name=GRIN>{{GRIN | accessdate=2008-03-17 }}</ref>\n|synonyms =\n*''Anthericum&nbsp;comosum'' <small>Thunb.</small>\n*''Hartwegia comosa'' <small>(Thunb.) [[Christian Gottfried Daniel Nees von Esenbeck|Nees]]</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Chlorophytum comosum''''', often called '''spider plant''' but also known as '''airplane plant''', '''St. Bernard's lily''', '''spider ivy''', '''ribbon plant''',<ref name=Poole1991/> and '''hen and chickens'''<ref name=Plantzafrica>{{cite web |url=http://www.plantzafrica.com/plantcd/chlorophytcom.htm |title=Chlorophytum comosum |website=PlantzAfrica.com |date=November 2012 |author=Ernst van Jaarsveld |publisher=South African National Biodiversity Institute |accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> is a [[species]] of [[perennial plant|perennial]] [[flowering plant]]. It is [[native plant|native]] to [[Tropical Africa|tropical]] and [[southern Africa]], but has become naturalized in other parts of the world, including [[western Australia]].<ref name=KewWC>{{Citation |title=World Checklist of Selected Plant Families |publisher=The Board of Trustees of the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]] |url=http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/home.do |accessdate=2011-09-26 }}, search for \"Chlorophytum comosum\"</ref><ref>Howell, J.T., P.H. Raven & P. Rubtzoff. 1958. Flora of San Francisco. Wasmann J. Biology 16:1-155.</ref>  ''Chlorophytum comosum'' is easy to grow as a [[houseplant]]; [[Variegation|variegated]] forms are the most popular.\n\n==Description==\n''Chlorophytum comosum'' grows to about {{convert|60|cm|in|0}} high. It has fleshy, [[Tuber#Root tubers|tuberous roots]], about {{convert|5|-|10|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} long. The long narrow leaves reach a length of {{convert|20|-|45|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} and are around {{convert|6|-|25|mm|in|1}} wide.<ref name=McCuneHardin>{{Citation |last=McCune |first=S. |last2=Hardin |first2=D. W. |year=1994 |contribution=''Chlorophytum comosum'' (Thunb.) Jacques |title=PlantNET - The Plant Information Network System of The Royal Botanic Gardens and Domain Trust |location=Sydney, Australia |publisher=The Royal Botanic Gardens and Domain Trust |url=http://plantnet.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/NSWfl.pl?page=nswfl&lvl=sp&name=Chlorophytum~comosum |accessdate=2011-09-27 |lastauthoramp=yes}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2006-12-09Chlorophytum07-03.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Flower of ''Chlorophytum comosum'' 'Vittatum']]\nFlowers are produced in a long branched [[inflorescence]], which can reach a length of up to {{convert|75|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} and eventually bends downwards. Flowers initially occur in clusters of 1\u20136 at intervals along the stem ([[scape (botany)|scape]]) of the inflorescence. Each cluster is at the base of a [[bract]], which ranges from {{convert|2|-|8|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} in length, becoming smaller towards the end of the inflorescence. Most of the flowers which are produced initially die off, so that the inflorescences are relatively sparsely flowered.<ref name=McCuneHardin/>\n\nIndividual flowers are greenish-white, borne on stalks ([[pedicel (botany)|pedicel]]s) some {{convert|4|-|8|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long. Each flower has six three-veined [[Tepal|tepals]] which are {{convert|6|-|9|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long, slightly hooded or boat-shaped at their tips. The [[stamen]]s consist of a [[pollen]]-producing anther about {{convert|3.5|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long with a filament about the same length or slightly longer. The central [[style (botany)|style]] is {{convert|3|-|8|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long. Seeds are produced in a [[capsule (botany)|capsule]] {{convert|3|-|8|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long on stalks (pedicels) which lengthen to up to {{convert|12|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}.<ref name=McCuneHardin/>\n\nThe inflorescences carry [[plantlets]] at the tips of their branches, which eventually droop and touch the soil, developing [[adventitious root]]s. The stems (scapes) of the inflorescence are called \"[[stolons]]\" in some sources, but this term is more correctly used for stems which do not bear flowers, and have roots at the [[plant stem|nodes]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Hickey, M. |author2=King, C. |year=2001 |title= The Cambridge Illustrated Glossary of Botanical Terms |publisher=Cambridge University Press }}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n''Chlorophytum&nbsp;comosum'' was first formally described by the Swedish naturalist [[Carl Peter Thunberg]] as ''Anthericum&nbsp;comosum'' in the 1794 volume of ''Prodromus Plantarum Capensium'', Thunberg's work on the plants of South Africa.<ref name=\"IPNI1\">{{IPNI|id=530288-1|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Thunber 1794\">Thunberg, Carl Peter. 1794. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3553183 ''Prodromus Plantarum Capensium''.] p. 63.</ref> It was subsequently moved to a number of different genera, including ''Phalangium'', ''[[Caesia]]'', ''Hartwegia'' <small>Nees</small> and ''Hollia'', before receiving its current placement in ''Chlorophytum'' by Jacques in 1862.<ref name=KewWC/>\n\nThe species has been confused with ''Chlorophytum capense'' <small>(L.) Voss</small> by some authors, but this is a different species.<ref name=GRIN/>\n\n===Intra-specific variation===\n[[File:2007-06-24Chlorophytum comosum04.jpg|thumb|175px|Fleshy roots of pot-grown ''Chlorophytum comosum'']]\n\nThere are three described varieties of the species: the [[autonym (botany)|autonym]] ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''comosum'' has strap-shaped narrow leaves and is found along forest margins, ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''bipindense'' has broader, [[petiole (botany)|petiolate]] leaves with stripes on the underside and the inflorescences are 2-3 times the length of the leaves, and ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''sparsiflorum'' also has broader leaves that narrow to the base and usually lacks a petiole and the striping on the underside of the leaf and the inflorescences are up to two times the length of the leaves. The latter two are rain forest-dwelling taxa that had earlier been described as separate species, but botanists Axel Dalberg Poulsen and Inger Nordal reduced the taxa to varieties of ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' in 2005.<ref name=\"Poulsen & Nordal 2005\">Poulsen, AD, and I Nordal. 2005. A phenetic analysis and revision of Guineo-Congolean rain forest taxa of ''Chlorophytum'' (Anthericaceae). ''Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society'', 148: 1-20.</ref>\n\nDelimitation of species boundaries within the genus ''Chlorophytum'' is reported to be difficult, possibly because of several evolutionary radiations into forest environments that led to morphological aspects that are too similar to reliably distinguish separate species. The evidence given to support this is the widespread distribution of most taxa in the genus and poor seed dispersal, leading to the conclusion of deeper evolutionary divergence among the taxa. [[File:Chlorophytum comosum 01.jpg|thumb|''C. comosum'' 'Variegatum']]\n\nThe three described [[variety (botany)|varieties]] in ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' could be an example of this [[convergent evolution]] of leaf shape among the forest-dwelling varieties from species of disparate origin, leading to the species ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' being [[polyphyletic]], instead of the traditional view of morphological divergence among the varieties within the species with the assumption of a common origin ([[monophyly]]). The widespread ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''comosum'' has slender, near linear leaves that lack a [[petiole (botany)|petiole]] similar to plants found in cultivation and is only found growing at the margins of the rain forest. The two other varieties, ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''sparsiflorum'' and ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''bipindense'', possess petioles and have broader leaves necessary for collecting more light in the shady Guineo-Congolean rain forest. A study published in 2005 used 16 morphological characters and was unable to delimit species boundaries among these three taxa, so they were relegated to varietal status.<ref name=\"Poulsen & Nordal 2005\" /> A follow-up study published in 2008 provided preliminary evidence from [[phylogenetics|phylogenetic analysis]] of [[plastid]] and nuclear DNA sequences that established samples from disparate collections sites identified as ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' were [[Polyphyly|polyphyletic]].<ref name=\"Bjora et al 2008\">Bjor\u00e5, CS, A Hemp, G Hoell, and I Nordal. 2008. A taxonomic and ecological analysis of two forest ''Chlorophytum'' taxa (Anthericaceae) on Mount Kilimanjaro, Tanzania. ''Plant Systematics and Evolution'', 274: 243-253.</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n''Chlorophytum comosum'' has a widespread native distribution in Africa, being native to six of the 10 [[World Geographical Scheme for Recording Plant Distributions]] regions of Africa (West Tropical Africa, West-Central Tropical Africa, Northeast Tropical Africa, East Tropical Africa, South Tropical Africa and Southern Africa).<ref name=\"KewWC\" />\n\n==Cultivation==\n[[File:Chlorophytum comosum Ampel.jpg|thumb|''Chlorophytum comosum'' 'Variegatum' in a hanging basket showing the plantlets]]\n\n''Chlorophytum comosum'' is a popular [[houseplant]]. The species with all-green leaves forms only a small proportion of plants sold. More common are two variegated cultivars:<ref name=Poole1991>{{Citation |last=Poole |first=R.T. |last2=Chase |first2=A.R. |last3=Osborne |first3=L.S. |year=1991 |title=Spider Plant Production Guide (CFREC-Apopka Foliage Plant Research Note RH-91-33) |publisher=Central Florida Research and Education Center, University of Florida |url=http://mrec.ifas.ufl.edu/foliage/folnotes/spider.htm |accessdate=2011-09-26 |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\n* ''C. comosum'' 'Vittatum' has mid-green leaves with a broad central white stripe. It is often sold in [[Hanging basket|hanging baskets]] to display the [[plantlet]]<nowiki/>s.<ref name=Poole1991/> The long stems are white.\n* ''C. comosum'' 'Variegatum' has darker green leaves with white margins. It is generally smaller than the previous cultivar.<ref name=Poole1991/> The long stems are green.\n\nBoth cultivars have gained the [[Royal Horticultural Society]]'s [[Award of Garden Merit]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=2315 | title=Chlorophytum comosum 'Variegatum' (v) &#124; variegated spider ivy/RHS Gardening}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=424 | title=Chlorophytum comosum 'Vittatum' (v) &#124; spider ivy 'Vittatum'/RHS Gardening}}</ref> (confirmed 2017).<ref>{{cite web  | url= https://www.rhs.org.uk/plants/pdfs/agm-lists/agm-ornamentals.pdf | title = AGM Plants - Ornamental | date = July 2017 | page = 18 | publisher = Royal Horticultural Society | accessdate = 24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nSpider plants are easy to grow, being able to thrive in a wide range of conditions. They will tolerate temperatures down to {{convert|35|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|disp=flip}}, but grow best at temperatures between {{convert|65|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|disp=flip}} and {{convert|90|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|disp=flip}}. Plants can be damaged by high [[fluoride]] or [[boron]] levels.<ref name=Poole1991/>\n\nThe [[NASA Clean Air Study]] determined that this plant was effective at removing common household air toxins [[formaldehyde]] and [[xylene]]. \n\nSpider plants have also been shown to reduce [[indoor air pollution]] in the form of [[formaldehyde]], and approximately 70 plants would neutralize the formaldehyde released by materials in a representative (ca. {{convert|160|m2|disp=sqbr|abbr=on}}) energy-efficient house, assuming each plant occupies a 3.8 L pot. <ref name=\"nasastudy\">{{cite journal |author1=Wolverton, B. C. |author2=McDonald, Rebecca C. |author3=Watkins, E. A. |date=1984 |url=http://www.greenenergyhelps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Wolverton-et-al-1984.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427225702/http://www.greenenergyhelps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Wolverton-et-al-1984.pdf |archivedate=April 27, 2015 |title=Foliage plants for removing indoor air pollutants from energy-efficient homes |journal=Economic Botany |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=224\u2013228 |doi=10.1007/BF02858837|hdl=2060/19860066312 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of air-filtering plants]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons-inline|Chlorophytum comosum|''Chlorophytum comosum''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1164349}}\n\n[[Category:Agavoideae]]\n[[Category:Flora of West Tropical Africa]]\n[[Category:Flora of West-Central Tropical Africa]]\n[[Category:Flora of Northeast Tropical Africa]]\n[[Category:Flora of East Tropical Africa]]\n[[Category:Flora of South Tropical Africa]]\n[[Category:Flora of Southern Africa]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Africa]]\n[[Category:House plants]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1794]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Peter Thunberg]]\n[[Category:Low light plants]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|taxon = Chlorophytum comosum\n|image = Hierbabuena 0611 Revised.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Chlorophytum comosum'' 'Vittatum'\n|authority = ([[Carl Peter Thunberg|Thunb.]]) [[Henri Antoine Jacques|Jacques]]<ref name=GRIN>{{GRIN | accessdate=2008-03-17 }}</ref>\n|synonyms =\n*''Anthericum&nbsp;comosum'' <small>Thunb.</small>\n*''Hartwegia comosa'' <small>(Thunb.) [[Christian Gottfried Daniel Nees von Esenbeck|Nees]]</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Chlorophytum comosum''''', often called '''spider plant''' but also known as '''airplane plant''', '''St. Bernard's lily''', '''spider ivy''', '''ribbon plant''',<ref name=Poole1991/> and '''hen and chickens'''<ref name=Plantzafrica>{{cite web |url=http://www.plantzafrica.com/plantcd/chlorophytcom.htm |title=Chlorophytum comosum |website=PlantzAfrica.com |date=November 2012 |author=Ernst van Jaarsveld |publisher=South African National Biodiversity Institute |accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> is a [[species]] of [[perennial plant|perennial]] [[flowering plant]]. It is [[native plant|native]] to [[Tropical Africa|tropical]] and [[southern Africa]], but has become naturalized in other parts of the world, including [[western Australia]].<ref name=KewWC>{{Citation |title=World Checklist of Selected Plant Families |publisher=The Board of Trustees of the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]] |url=http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/home.do |accessdate=2011-09-26 }}, search for \"Chlorophytum comosum\"</ref><ref>Howell, J.T., P.H. Raven & P. Rubtzoff. 1958. Flora of San Francisco. Wasmann J. Biology 16:1-155.</ref>  ''Chlorophytum comosum'' is easy to grow as a [[houseplant]]; [[Variegation|variegated]] forms are the most popular.\n\n==Description==\n''Chlorophytum comosum'' grows to about {{convert|60|cm|in|0}} high. It has fleshy, [[Tuber#Root tubers|tuberous roots]], about {{convert|5|-|10|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} long. The long narrow leaves reach a length of {{convert|20|-|45|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} and are around {{convert|6|-|25|mm|in|1}} wide.<ref name=McCuneHardin>{{Citation |last=McCune |first=S. |last2=Hardin |first2=D. W. |year=1994 |contribution=''Chlorophytum comosum'' (Thunb.) Jacques |title=PlantNET - The Plant Information Network System of The Royal Botanic Gardens and Domain Trust |location=Sydney, Australia |publisher=The Royal Botanic Gardens and Domain Trust |url=http://plantnet.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/NSWfl.pl?page=nswfl&lvl=sp&name=Chlorophytum~comosum |accessdate=2011-09-27 |lastauthoramp=yes}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2006-12-09Chlorophytum07-03.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Flower of ''Chlorophytum comosum'' 'Vittatum']]\nFlowers are produced in a long branched [[inflorescence]], which can reach a length of up to {{convert|75|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} and eventually bends downwards. Flowers initially occur in clusters of 1\u20136 at intervals along the stem ([[scape (botany)|scape]]) of the inflorescence. Each cluster is at the base of a [[bract]], which ranges from {{convert|2|-|8|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} in length, becoming smaller towards the end of the inflorescence. Most of the flowers which are produced initially die off, so that the inflorescences are relatively sparsely flowered.<ref name=McCuneHardin/>\n\nIndividual flowers are greenish-white, borne on stalks ([[pedicel (botany)|pedicel]]s) some {{convert|4|-|8|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long. Each flower has six three-veined [[Tepal|tepals]] which are {{convert|6|-|9|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long, slightly hooded or boat-shaped at their tips. The [[stamen]]s consist of a [[pollen]]-producing anther about {{convert|3.5|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long with a filament about the same length or slightly longer. The central [[style (botany)|style]] is {{convert|3|-|8|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long. Seeds are produced in a [[capsule (botany)|capsule]] {{convert|3|-|8|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} long on stalks (pedicels) which lengthen to up to {{convert|12|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}.<ref name=McCuneHardin/>\n\nThe inflorescences carry [[plantlets]] at the tips of their branches, which eventually droop and touch the soil, developing [[Adventitious Roots|adventitious roots]]. The stems (scapes) of the inflorescence are called \"[[stolons]]\" in some sources, but this term is more correctly used for stems which do not bear flowers, and have roots at the [[plant stem|nodes]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Hickey, M. |author2=King, C. |year=2001 |title= The Cambridge Illustrated Glossary of Botanical Terms |publisher=Cambridge University Press }}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n''Chlorophytum&nbsp;comosum'' was first formally described by the Swedish naturalist [[Carl Peter Thunberg]] as ''Anthericum&nbsp;comosum'' in the 1794 volume of ''Prodromus Plantarum Capensium'', Thunberg's work on the plants of South Africa.<ref name=\"IPNI1\">{{IPNI|id=530288-1|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Thunber 1794\">Thunberg, Carl Peter. 1794. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3553183 ''Prodromus Plantarum Capensium''.] p. 63.</ref> It was subsequently moved to a number of different genera, including ''Phalangium'', ''[[Caesia]]'', ''Hartwegia'' <small>Nees</small> and ''Hollia'', before receiving its current placement in ''Chlorophytum'' by Jacques in 1862.<ref name=KewWC/>\n\nThe species has been confused with ''Chlorophytum capense'' <small>(L.) Voss</small> by some authors, but this is a different species.<ref name=GRIN/>\n\n===Intra-specific variation===\n[[File:2007-06-24Chlorophytum comosum04.jpg|thumb|175px|Fleshy roots of pot-grown ''Chlorophytum comosum'']]\n\nThere are three described varieties of the species: the [[autonym (botany)|autonym]] ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''comosum'' has strap-shaped narrow leaves and is found along forest margins, ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''bipindense'' has broader, [[petiole (botany)|petiolate]] leaves with stripes on the underside and the inflorescences are 2-3 times the length of the leaves, and ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''sparsiflorum'' also has broader leaves that narrow to the base and usually lacks a petiole and the striping on the underside of the leaf and the inflorescences are up to two times the length of the leaves. The latter two are rain forest-dwelling taxa that had earlier been described as separate species, but botanists Axel Dalberg Poulsen and Inger Nordal reduced the taxa to varieties of ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' in 2005.<ref name=\"Poulsen & Nordal 2005\">Poulsen, AD, and I Nordal. 2005. A phenetic analysis and revision of Guineo-Congolean rain forest taxa of ''Chlorophytum'' (Anthericaceae). ''Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society'', 148: 1-20.</ref>\n\nDelimitation of species boundaries within the genus ''Chlorophytum'' is reported to be difficult, possibly because of several evolutionary radiations into forest environments that led to morphological aspects that are too similar to reliably distinguish separate species. The evidence given to support this is the widespread distribution of most taxa in the genus and poor seed dispersal, leading to the conclusion of deeper evolutionary divergence among the taxa. [[File:Chlorophytum comosum 01.jpg|thumb|''C. comosum'' 'Variegatum']]\n\nThe three described [[variety (botany)|varieties]] in ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' could be an example of this [[convergent evolution]] of leaf shape among the forest-dwelling varieties from species of disparate origin, leading to the species ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' being [[polyphyletic]], instead of the traditional view of morphological divergence among the varieties within the species with the assumption of a common origin ([[monophyly]]). The widespread ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''comosum'' has slender, near linear leaves that lack a [[petiole (botany)|petiole]] similar to plants found in cultivation and is only found growing at the margins of the rain forest. The two other varieties, ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''sparsiflorum'' and ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' var. ''bipindense'', possess petioles and have broader leaves necessary for collecting more light in the shady Guineo-Congolean rain forest. A study published in 2005 used 16 morphological characters and was unable to delimit species boundaries among these three taxa, so they were relegated to varietal status.<ref name=\"Poulsen & Nordal 2005\" /> A follow-up study published in 2008 provided preliminary evidence from [[phylogenetics|phylogenetic analysis]] of [[plastid]] and nuclear DNA sequences that established samples from disparate collections sites identified as ''C.&nbsp;comosum'' were [[Polyphyly|polyphyletic]].<ref name=\"Bjora et al 2008\">Bjor\u00e5, CS, A Hemp, G Hoell, and I Nordal. 2008. A taxonomic and ecological analysis of two forest ''Chlorophytum'' taxa (Anthericaceae) on Mount Kilimanjaro, Tanzania. ''Plant Systematics and Evolution'', 274: 243-253.</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n''Chlorophytum comosum'' has a widespread native distribution in Africa, being native to six of the 10 [[World Geographical Scheme for Recording Plant Distributions]] regions of Africa (West Tropical Africa, West-Central Tropical Africa, Northeast Tropical Africa, East Tropical Africa, South Tropical Africa and Southern Africa).<ref name=\"KewWC\" />\n\n==Cultivation==\n[[File:Chlorophytum comosum Ampel.jpg|thumb|''Chlorophytum comosum'' 'Variegatum' in a hanging basket showing the plantlets]]\n\n''Chlorophytum comosum'' is a popular [[houseplant]]. The species with all-green leaves forms only a small proportion of plants sold. More common are two variegated cultivars:<ref name=Poole1991>{{Citation |last=Poole |first=R.T. |last2=Chase |first2=A.R. |last3=Osborne |first3=L.S. |year=1991 |title=Spider Plant Production Guide (CFREC-Apopka Foliage Plant Research Note RH-91-33) |publisher=Central Florida Research and Education Center, University of Florida |url=http://mrec.ifas.ufl.edu/foliage/folnotes/spider.htm |accessdate=2011-09-26 |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\n* ''C. comosum'' 'Vittatum' has mid-green leaves with a broad central white stripe. It is often sold in [[Hanging basket|hanging baskets]] to display the [[plantlet]]<nowiki/>s.<ref name=Poole1991/> The long stems are white.\n* ''C. comosum'' 'Variegatum' has darker green leaves with white margins. It is generally smaller than the previous cultivar.<ref name=Poole1991/> The long stems are green.\n\nBoth cultivars have gained the [[Royal Horticultural Society]]'s [[Award of Garden Merit]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=2315 | title=Chlorophytum comosum 'Variegatum' (v) &#124; variegated spider ivy/RHS Gardening}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=424 | title=Chlorophytum comosum 'Vittatum' (v) &#124; spider ivy 'Vittatum'/RHS Gardening}}</ref> (confirmed 2017).<ref>{{cite web  | url= https://www.rhs.org.uk/plants/pdfs/agm-lists/agm-ornamentals.pdf | title = AGM Plants - Ornamental | date = July 2017 | page = 18 | publisher = Royal Horticultural Society | accessdate = 24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nSpider plants are easy to grow, being able to thrive in a wide range of conditions. They will tolerate temperatures down to {{convert|35|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|disp=flip}}, but grow best at temperatures between {{convert|65|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|disp=flip}} and {{convert|90|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|disp=flip}}. Plants can be damaged by high [[fluoride]] or [[boron]] levels.<ref name=Poole1991/>\n\nThe [[NASA Clean Air Study]] determined that this plant was effective at removing common household air toxins [[formaldehyde]] and [[xylene]]. \n\nSpider plants have also been shown to reduce [[indoor air pollution]] in the form of [[formaldehyde]], and approximately 70 plants would neutralize the formaldehyde released by materials in a representative (ca. {{convert|160|m2|disp=sqbr|abbr=on}}) energy-efficient house, assuming each plant occupies a 3.8 L pot. <ref name=\"nasastudy\">{{cite journal |author1=Wolverton, B. C. |author2=McDonald, Rebecca C. |author3=Watkins, E. A. |date=1984 |url=http://www.greenenergyhelps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Wolverton-et-al-1984.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427225702/http://www.greenenergyhelps.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Wolverton-et-al-1984.pdf |archivedate=April 27, 2015 |title=Foliage plants for removing indoor air pollutants from energy-efficient homes |journal=Economic Botany |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=224\u2013228 |doi=10.1007/BF02858837|hdl=2060/19860066312 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of air-filtering plants]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons-inline|Chlorophytum comosum|''Chlorophytum comosum''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1164349}}\n\n[[Category:Agavoideae]]\n[[Category:Flora of West Tropical Africa]]\n[[Category:Flora of West-Central Tropical Africa]]\n[[Category:Flora of Northeast Tropical Africa]]\n[[Category:Flora of East Tropical Africa]]\n[[Category:Flora of South Tropical Africa]]\n[[Category:Flora of Southern Africa]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Africa]]\n[[Category:House plants]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1794]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Peter Thunberg]]\n[[Category:Low light plants]]\n", "name_user": "Hankwang", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription:link toadventitious rootrather thanAdventitious Root", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chlorophytum_comosum"}
