MX/Shorcan Energy Brokers |ref={{SfnRef|TMX/Shorcan Energy Brokers}}}}\n*{{citation |ref={{SfnRef|Tobben|Murtaugh|2014}} |title=Suncor Looks to Europe as Outlet for Canadian Crude |first1=Sheela |last1=Tobben |first2=Dan |last2=Murtaugh |date=25 September 2014 |accessdate=2 December 2014 |url=http://washpost.bloomberg.com/Story?docId=1376-NCDK5T6VDKHS01-5G0TTI1G4S53PO0CO0MUA6D92Q |publisher=Washington Post }}\n* {{citation |ref={{SfnRef|Toledo Blade|2010}} |title=BP-Husky OKs $2.5B for project to boost oil volume|url=http://www.toledoblade.com/local/2010/12/02/BP-Husky-OKs-2-5B-for-project-to-boost-oil-volume.html |work=Toledo Blade |date=1 December 2010|accessdate=13 December 2013}}\n* {{citation |ref={{SfnRef|TransCanada|2013}} |url=http://www.energyeastpipeline.com/about/the-project/#sthash.4aByrc7v.dpuf|title=About Energy East Pipeline|work=TransCanada|year=2013|accessdate=20 August 2013}}\n* {{citation |ref={{SfnRef|Tweh|2012}} |title=BP CEO: We want your trust |first=Bowdeyah|last= Tweh|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/business/local/bp-ceo-we-want-your-trust/article_ab9219fe-47c1-5f0c-ad1f-a042fa060152.html |publisher=nwi.com |date=13 January 2012 |accessdate=30 July 2012}}\n<!--U-->\n* {{citation |url=http://usdpartners.com/terminal/hardisty/ |title=Hardisty Terminal, Alberta, Canada |work=USD Partners |year=2015 |accessdate=2 June 2015 |location=|ref={{SfnRef|USD Partners|2015}}}}\n* {{cite web |ref={{SfnRef|U.S. Energy Information Agency|2013}} |title=Refinery Rankings|url=http://www.eia.doe.gov/neic/rankings/refineries.htm|work=U.S. Energy Information Agency|accessdate=11 August 2013 |year=2013}}\n<!--V-->\n* {{citation |ref={{SfnRef|Van Loon|2013}}|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-01-21/world-s-cheapest-oil-crimps-alberta-budget-with-price-gap.html|publisher=Bloomberg| title=World's Cheapest Oil Crimps Alberta Budget With Price Gap| first=Jeremy| last=Van Loon| date=21 January 2013|accessdate=13 December 2013}}\n* {{citation |ref={{SfnRef|Vanderklippe|2013}} | title=Oil differential darkens Alberta's budget| first=Nathan |last=Vanderklippe| location=Calgary, Alberta| publisher=Globe and Mail| url=http://m.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/industry-news/energy-and-resources/oil-differential-darkens-albertas-budget/article7647602/?service=mobile| date=22 January 2013}}\n* {{citation |ref={{SfnRef|Vanderklippe|2013b}} |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/industry-news/energy-and-resources/suncors-15-billion-writedown-puts-oil-sands-project-in-jeopardy/article8287055/ |publisher=The Globe and Mail|date=6 February 2013b |first=Nathan|last=Vanderklippe |title=Suncor's $1.5-billion writedown puts oil sands project in jeopardy|accessdate=13 December 2013}}\n<!--W-->\n* {{citation |ref={{SfnRef|Welsch|Harvey|2013}}| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-02-11/consumers-co-op-shuts-coker-at-saskatchewan-plant-after-fire-1-.html| title=Consumers Co-op Shuts Coker at Saskatchewan Plant After Fire| first1=Edward| last1=Welsch|first2=Christine| last2=Harvey| date=11 February 2013| publisher=Bloomberg}}\n*{{citation  |ref={{SfnRef|Welsch|2013}} |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-14/canadian-oils-gain-on-expectation-of-rising-u-s-refinery-demand.html |title=Canadian Oils Gain on Expectation of Rising U.S. Refinery Demand |first=Edward |last=Welsch |date=14 May 2013 |accessdate=25 March 2015}}\n* {{citation |url=http://www.bnn.ca/News/2015/5/5/Trains-shift-to-carry-less-volatile-crude.aspx |title=Trains shift to carry less-volatile crude |date=5 May 2015 |accessdate=2 June 2015 |work=BNN via Reuters |first=Nia |last=Williams|ref={{SfnRef|Williams|2015}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Petroleum industry}}\n{{Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin|Fields=yes}}\n\n[[Category:Benchmark crude oils]]\n[[Category:Oil and gas markets]]\n[[Category:Athabasca oil sands| ]]\n[[Category:Proposed energy projects]]\n[[Category:Bituminous sands]]\n[[Category:Petroleum geology]]\n[[Category:Petroleum industry]]\n[[Category:Unconventional oil]]\n[[Category:Economy of Canada]]\n", "name_user": "M.nelson", "label": "safe", "comment": "rm duplicate refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Canadian_Select"}
{"title_page": "App store", "text_new": "'''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/ Brand New Softwares ,Apps & Games]'''{{short description|Digital distribution platform for application softwares}}\n{{pp-pc1|expiry=July 30, 2020}}\n{{About|the concept|the store for Apple iOS apps|App Store (iOS)|the store for Apple Mac apps|App Store (macOS)}}\nAn '''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/03/pubg-mobile-kr-0170-apk-for-pc-download.html app store]''' (or '''app marketplace''') is a type of [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/03/pubg-mobile-kr-0170-apk-for-pc-download.html digital distribution] platform for computer software called [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/03/mobile-legends-bang-bang-new-game-for.html Applications,] often in a mobile context. Apps provide a specific set of functions which, by definition, do not include the running of the computer itself. Complex software designed for use on a [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/03/mobile-legends-bang-bang-new-game-for.html '''personal computer'''], for example, may have a related app designed for use on a [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/03/mobile-legends-bang-bang-new-game-for.html '''''mobile device.'''''] Today apps are normally designed to run on a specific [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/03/mobile-legends-bang-bang-new-game-for.html operating system]\u2014such as the contemporary [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/03/mobile-legends-bang-bang-new-game-for.html '''iOS'''], [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/03/mobile-legends-bang-bang-new-game-for.html '''macOS'''], '''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/03/mobile-legends-bang-bang-new-game-for.html Windows] or [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/03/mobile-legends-bang-bang-new-game-for.html Android]'''\u2014but in the past [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/03/pubg-mobile-kr-0170-apk-for-pc-download.html mobile carriers] had their own portals for apps and related media content.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.telecomcircle.com/2009/05/the-economics-of-mobile-application-stores/ | title=The Economics of Mobile Application Store| date=2009-05-17}}</ref>\n\n=='''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/ Best apps Games & Softwares Store]'''  ==\nAn app store is any digital storefront intended to allow search and review of software titles or other media offered for sale electronically. Critically, the application storefront itself provides a secure, uniform experience that automates the electronic purchase, decryption and installation of software applications or other digital media. \n\nApp stores typically organize the apps they offer based on: the function(s) provided by the app (including games, multimedia or productivity), the device for which the app was designed, and the operating system on which the app will run.\n\nApp stores typically take the form of an [[Online shopping|online store]], where [[End-user|users]] can browse through these different app categories, view information about each app (such as reviews or ratings), and acquire the app (including app purchase, if necessary \u2013 many apps are offered at no cost). The selected app is offered as an automatic download, after which the app installs. Some app stores may also include a system to [[kill switch|automatically remove an installed program]] from devices under certain conditions, with the goal of protecting the user against malicious software.<ref name=cw-remotedisable>{{cite web|title=Microsoft: We can remotely delete Windows 8 apps|url=http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/9222518/Microsoft_We_can_remotely_delete_Windows_8_apps |work=[[Computerworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] |accessdate=8 October 2013|date=2011-12-08 }}</ref>\n\nApp stores typically provide a way for users to give reviews and ratings. Those reviews are useful for other users, for developers and for app store owners. Users can select the best apps based on ratings, developers get feedback on what features are praised or disliked and finally, app store owners can detect bad apps and malicious developers by automatically analyzing the reviews with data mining techniques.<ref>{{Cite book  |doi=10.1109/MobileSoft.2015.8|isbn=978-0-7695-5566-9|chapter=A Recommender System of Buggy App Checkers for App Store Moderators|title=2015 2nd ACM International Conference on Mobile Software Engineering and Systems|pages=1\u201311|year=2015|last1=Gomez|first1=Maria|last2=Rouvoy|first2=Romain|last3=Monperrus|first3=Martin|last4=Seinturier|first4=Lionel|chapter-url=https://hal.inria.fr/hal-01079681/file/RR_BuggyAppCheckers-v2.pdf}}</ref>\n\nMany app stores are [[curator|curated]] by their owners, requiring that submissions of prospective apps go through an approval process. These apps are inspected for compliance with certain guidelines (such as those for [[quality control]] and [[censorship]]), including the requirement that a [[Commission (remuneration)|commission]] be collected on each sale of a paid app. Some app stores provides feedback to developers: number of installations, issues in the field (latency, crash, etc.).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gomez |first1=Maria |last2=Adams |first2=Bram |last3=Maalej |first3=Walid |last4=Monperrus |first4=Martin |last5=Rouvoy |first5=Romain |title=App Store 2.0: From Crowdsourced Information to Actionable Feedback in Mobile Ecosystems |journal=IEEE Software |date=March 2017 |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=81\u201389 |doi=10.1109/ms.2017.46 |url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01406422/document|arxiv=1807.00518 }}</ref>\n\nResearchers have proposed new features for app stores. For instance, the app store can deliver a unique [[software diversity|diversified version]] of the app for sake of security.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Franz |first1=Michael |title=E unibus pluram: massive-scale software diversity as a defense mechanism |date=21 September 2010 |pages=7\u201316 |doi=10.1145/1900546.1900550 | publisher=ACM}}</ref> The app store can also orchestrate monitoring and bug fixing to detect and repair crashes in applications.<ref>{{cite book |doi=10.1109/icse.2015.195 |chapter-url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01105173/document|isbn=978-1-4799-1934-5 |chapter=When App Stores Listen to the Crowd to Fight Bugs in the Wild|title=2015 IEEE/ACM 37th IEEE International Conference on Software Engineering|pages=567\u2013570|year=2015|last1=Gomez|first1=Maria|last2=Martineza|first2=Matias|last3=Monperrus|first3=Martin|last4=Rouvoy|first4=Romain|url=https://hal.inria.fr/hal-01105173/file/NIER15-preprint.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Precursors===\nThe [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/ '''Electronic AppWrappe'''r]<ref name=\"CT-AW3\">[http://www.kevra.org/TheBestOfNext/SWCatalogs/page274/page274.html Electronic AppWrapper]. Kevra.org. Retrieved on 2013-11-22.</ref> was the first commercial electronic software distribution catalog to collectively manage encryption and provide digital rights for apps and digital media<ref name=PR-AW3>[https://groups.google.com/group/comp.sys.next.announce/msg/56aacf1318e577ce  AppWrapper Volume1 Issue 3 Ships]. Groups.google.com. Retrieved on 2013-11-22.</ref> (issue #3 was the app store originally demonstrated to Steve Jobs at NeXTWorld EXPO).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carey|first1=Richard|title=Electronic Recollections, By Ricard Carey|url=http://appstorey.com/2015/07/17/electronic-recollections-by-ricard-carey/|website=AppStorey|publisher=Richard Carey|date=2015-07-17}}</ref> While a Senior Editor at [[NeXTWORLD Magazine]], [[Simson Garfinkel]], rated The [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/ '''Electronic AppWrapper'''] 4 3/4 Cubes (out of 5), in his formal review. Paget's [[Electronic AppWrapper]] was named a finalist in the highly  competitive InVision Multimedia '93 awards in January, 1993 and won the Best of Breed award for Content and Information at NeXTWORLD Expo in May, 1993.<ref name=NW-AW3>Ruby, Dan (August 1993) [http://www.blackholeinc.com/Library/93%20Aug.html Our First Annual Awards for NEXTSTEP Product Excellence]. NeXTWORLD.</ref>\n[[File:The Electronic AppWrapper 3D Reality Screen Shot.png|thumb|A Screen Shot of Stone Design's 3DReality running on the Electronic AppWrapper, the first app store]]\nPrior to the Electronic AppWrapper which first shipped in 1992 people were used to software distributed via floppy disks or CD-ROMs, one could even download software using a web browser or command-line tools. Many [[Linux]] [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html '''distributions'''] and other [[Unix-like]] systems provide a tool known as a [[package management system|package manager]], which allows a user to automatically manage the software installed on their systems (including both operating system components and third-party software) using [[command line]] tools{{emdash}}new software (and the packages required for its proper operation) can be retrieved from local or remote [[Web mirror|mirrors]] and automatically installed in a single process. Notable package managers in Unix-like operating systems have included [[FreeBSD Ports]] (1994), [[pkgsrc]] (1997), [[Debian]]'s [[Advanced Packaging Tool|APT]] (1998), [[Yellowdog Updater, Modified|YUM]], and [[Gentoo Linux|Gentoo]]'s [[Portage (software)|Portage]] (which unlike most package managers, distributes packages containing [[source code]] that is automatically [[compiler|compiled]] instead of [[executable]]s). Some package managers have [[graphical user interface|graphical]] front-end software which can be used to browse available packages and perform operations, such as [[Synaptic (software)|Synaptic]] (which is often used as a front-end for APT).\n\nIn 1996, the SUSE Linux distribution has [[YaST]] as frontend for its own app repository. Mandriva Linux has [[urpmi]] with GUI frontend called [[Rpmdrake]]. Fedora and [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html '''Red Hat Enterprise Linux'''] has [[Yellowdog Updater, Modified|YUM]] in 2003 as a successor of YUP (developed at '''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html Duke University for Red Hat Linux).]'''\n\nIn 1997, BeDepot a third-party app store and package manager ([[Software Valet]]) for [[BeOS]] was launched, which operated until 2001. It was eventually acquired by Be Inc. BeDepot allowed for both commercial and free apps as well as handling updates\n\nIn 1998, Information Technologies India Ltd (ITIL) launched Palmix, a web based app store exclusively for mobile and handheld devices. Palmix sold apps for the three major PDA platforms of the time: the Palm OS based Palm Pilots, Windows CE based devices, and Psion Epoc handhelds.<ref name=Palmix>{{cite web|title=A one stop shop for so-oft-ware for Palmtops and Handhelds |url=http://www.palmix.itil.com/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000818162218/http://www.palmix.itil.com/ |archivedate=August 18, 2000 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, [[NTT DoCoMo]] launched [[i-mode]], the first integrated online app store for mobile phones, gaining nationwide popularity in [[Japanese mobile phone culture]]. DoCoMo used a revenue-sharing business model, allowing content creators and app providers to keep up to 91% of revenue.<ref>Mary J. Cronin (2010), [https://books.google.com/books?id=70m6XdOtnG0C&pg=PA135 ''Smart Products, Smarter Services: Strategies for Embedded Control'', p. 135], [[Cambridge University Press]]</ref> Other operators outside Japan also made their own portals after this, such as [[Vodafone live!]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/vodafone-calls-mobiles-go-live/508233 |title = Vodafone calls on mobiles to go Live!}}</ref> At this time mobile phone manufacturer [[Nokia]] also introduced carrier-free downloadable content with [[Club Nokia]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB99055184153156198 | title='Club Nokia' Service Could Put Firm in Awkward Position with Operators| newspaper=Wall Street Journal| date=2001-05-23| last1=Newswires| first1=Buster Kantrowdow Jones}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2001, [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint PCS]] launched the Ringers & More Wireless Download Service for their then-new 3G wireless network. This allowed subscribers to the Sprint PCS mobile phone network to download ringtones, wallpaper, J2ME applications and later full music tracks to certain phones. The user interface worked through a web browser on the desktop computer, and a version was available through the handset.<ref name=sprintpcs>{{cite web|title=PRS Newswire: Sprint Customers Will Soon Personalize their Wireless Phones with New Sprint PCS Ringers & More(SM) Wireless Download Service|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sprint-customers-will-soon-personalize-their-wireless-phones-with-new-sprint-pcs-ringers--moresm-wireless-download-service-74513067.html|accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the commercial Linux distribution [[Linspire]] (then known as LindowsOS{{emdash}}which was founded by [[Michael Robertson (businessman)|Michael Robertson]], founder of [[MP3.com]]) introduced an app store known as [[CNR (software)|Click'N'Run]] (CNR). For an annual subscription fee, users could perform one-click installation of free and paid apps through the CNR software. [[Doc Searls]] believed that the ease-of-use of CNR could help make [[desktop Linux]] a feasible reality.<ref name=lm-cnr>{{cite magazine|title=Click-N-Run: an Easier Future for Customers?|url=http://www.linuxjournal.com/article/6718|magazine=Linux Journal|accessdate=13 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 [[Handango]] introduced the first on-device app store for finding, installing and buying software for smartphones. App download and purchasing are completed directly on the device so sync with a computer is not necessary. Description, rating and screenshot are available for any app.\n\nIn 2005 [[Nokia 770 Internet Tablet]] has graphical frontend for its app repository to easily install app (its [[Maemo]] was based on [[Debian]]). Later Nokia also introduced [[Nokia Catalogs]], later known as Nokia Download!, for [[Symbian]] smartphones which had access to downloadable apps\u2014originally via third-parties like Handango or [[Jamba!]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://darlamack.blogs.com/darlamack/2005/12/nokia_catalog_a.html |title = Nokia S60 News and Reviews}}</ref> but from mid-2006 Nokia were offering their own content via the Nokia Content Discoverer.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.geoconnexion.com/news/nokia-content-discoverer |title = Nokia Content Discoverer &#124;\u00a0GeoConnexion}}</ref>\n\nThe popular Linux distribution [[Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu]] (also based on Debian) introduced its own graphical software manager known as the [[Ubuntu Software Center]] on version 9.10 as a replacement for Synaptic.<ref name=itpro-karmic>{{cite web|title=Ubuntu 9.10 review: Karmic Koala|url=http://www.itpro.co.uk/617119/ubuntu-910-review-karmic-koala/page/0/1|publisher=ITPro.com|accessdate=15 February 2013}}</ref>  On Ubuntu 10.10, released in October 2010, the Software Center expanded beyond only offering existing software from its repositories by adding the ability to purchase certain apps (which, at launch, was limited to [[Fluendo]]'s licensed [[DVD]] [[codec]]s).<ref name=ubuntu-1010apps>{{cite web|title=Review: Ubuntu 10.10 builds on app store, cloud service strengths|url=http://www.desktoplinux.com/news/NS2360404946.html|publisher=DesktopLinux.com|accessdate=15 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] released [[iOS|iPhone OS]] 2.0 in July 2008 for the [[iPhone]], together with the [[iOS App Store|App Store]], officially introducing third-party app development and distribution to the platform. The service allows users to purchase and download new apps for their device through either the App Store on the device, or through the [[iTunes Store]] on the [[iTunes]] desktop software.<ref name=pcw-appstorefuture>{{cite magazine|title=What the App Store Future Means for Developers and Users|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/227961/what_app_store_future_means_for_developers_and_users.html|magazine=PC World|date=May 16, 2011|author=Beckman, Mel }}</ref><ref name=wsj-breaking>{{cite news|title=Breaking Apple's Grip on the iPhone|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123629876097346481|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=March 6, 2009|author=Yukari Iwatani Kane}}</ref> While Apple has been criticized by some for how it operates the App Store, it has been a major financial success for the company.<ref name=\"40bill\">{{cite web|publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|title=App Store Tops 40 Billion Downloads with Almost Half in 2012|url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2013/01/07App-Store-Tops-40-Billion-Downloads-with-Almost-Half-in-2012.html|date=2013-01-07}}</ref> The popularity of Apple's App Store led to the rise of the generic term \"app store\", as well as the introduction of [[List of mobile software distribution platforms|equivalent marketplaces]] by competing mobile operating systems: the [[Google Play|Android Market]] (later renamed to Google Play) launched alongside the release of the first [[Android (operating system)|Android]] smartphone (the [[HTC Dream]]) in September 2008,<ref name=cnet-androidlaunch>{{cite web|title=Hype builds for Android phone launch|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-10042908-94.html|website=CNET|date= September 16, 2008|author=Reardon, Marguerite }}</ref> [[BlackBerry]]'s [[BlackBerry World|App World]] launched in April 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-17938_105-10188400-1.html?tag=mncol;txt |title=RIM store crowned BlackBerry App World |author=Cha, Bonnie |publisher=CNET News |date=2009-03-04 |accessdate=2009-03-09}}</ref><ref name=pcw-ios2>{{cite magazine|title=Apple Releases iPhone OS 2.0 Update|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/148247/iphone_2.html|magazine=PC World|accessdate=13 February 2013|date=2008-07-11}}</ref> as well as [[Nokia]]'s [[Ovi Store]] and [[Microsoft]]'s [[Windows Marketplace for Mobile]] both launching that year too.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.mobilefun.co.uk/blog/2009/05/nokia-ovi-store-now-available/ |title = Nokia Ovi Store now available|date = 2009-05-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/microsoft-opens-windows-marketplace-for-mobile-with-246-apps/ |title = Microsoft opens Windows Marketplace for Mobile with 246 apps}}</ref>\n\n==[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/ \"App Store\" Best Store of The Word]==\n{{See also|Apple Inc. litigation#Amazon \"App Store\"}}\n\nDue to its popularity, the term \"app store\" (first used by the [[Electronic AppWrapper]]<ref name=\"CT-AW3\" /> and later popularized by [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s [[iOS App Store|App Store]] for [[iOS]] devices) has frequently been used as a [[generic trademark]] to refer to other distribution platforms of a similar nature. Apple asserted [[trademark]] claims over the phrase, and filed a trademark registration for \"App Store\" in 2008. In 2011, Apple [[Apple Inc. litigation#Amazon \"App Store\"|sued]] both [[Amazon (company)|Amazon.com]] (which runs the '''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html Amazon Appstore]''' for Android-based devices) and [[GetJar]] (who has offered its services since 2004) for '''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html trademark infringement and false advertising]''' regarding the use of the term \"app store\" to refer to their services.<ref name=bgr-getjar>{{cite web|title=GetJar responds to Apple's cease-and-desist letter over 'App Store' name|url=http://bgr.com/2011/07/11/getjar-responds-to-apples-cease-and-desist-letter-over-app-store-name/|publisher=BGR|accessdate=13 February 2013|date=2011-07-11}}</ref> [[Microsoft]] filed multiple objections against Apple's attempt to register the name as a trademark, considering it to already be a generic term.<ref name=pcmag-msappstore>{{cite magazine|title=Microsoft Files Another Objection in Apple's 'App Store' Trademark Case|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2382855,00.asp|magazine=PC Magazine|date= March 30, 2011|author=Yin, Sara }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Apple's claims were rejected by a US District judge, who argued that the company presented no evidence that Amazon had \"[attempted] to mimic Apple's site or advertising\", or communicated that its service \"possesses the characteristics and qualities that the public has come to expect from the Apple APP STORE and/or Apple products\"<ref name=ars-rejected>{{cite web|title=No app for that: Apple's false ad suit over Amazon Appstore thrown out|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/01/no-app-for-that-apples-false-ad-suit-over-amazon-appstore-thrown-out/|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> In July 2013, Apple dropped its case.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bostic |first=Kevin |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/13/07/09/apple-drops-app-store-lawsuit-against-amazon-says-no-need-to-pursue-case |title=Apple drops 'App Store' lawsuit against Amazon, says no need to pursue case |publisher=Appleinsider.com |date=2013-07-09 |accessdate=2014-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*'''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/ Electronic commerce]'''\n*[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html '''Digital distribution in video games''']\n*'''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/ Comparison of mobile operating systems]'''\n*[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html '''App store optimization''']\n*[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/ List of Android app stores]\n* [[List of mobile software distribution platforms]]\n**'''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/ App Store (iOS), iOS app approvals, App Store (watchOS), App Store (iMessage)]'''\n** [[Google Play]]\n** [[Microsoft Store (digital)]]\n* Desktop software distribution platforms\n**[[AppStream]]\n** [[Chrome Web Store]]\n** [[App Store (macOS)]], [[App Store (tvOS)]]\n**[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html '''Microsoft Store (digital)''']\n** [[Setapp]]\n** [[Steam (software)|Steam]]\n** [[Ubuntu Software Center]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n=== '''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html Team Fight Strategy: A Statement of the League of Legends Strategy Game:]''' ===\nThe creator of '''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html League of Legends, a rival sports PVP]''' strategy automaker, assemble an army of your favorite champions into the Team of Fight Tactics.\n\nIn Team Fight strategy, you will be drafted, deployed, and upgraded to a rotating roster of League of Legends Champions, in a round table survival battle. Spread destruction with devils, free from fear, or align with wardens. The strategy is entrusted to you.\n\n==== '''Fight it:''' ====\nGet your opponents outplayed and out of the list by preparing for the Elite Squad of the League of Legends Champions for your competition. Random drafts and game events ensure that no two matches are played at all.\n\n==== '''Strategy and survival:''' ====\nPermanent free-to-play updates and content reduction ensure a fresh, time-consuming meta and unlimited strategic depth.\n\n==== '''Get up and go:''' ====\nCross-Platform Support Monsanto Plug out your friends (and crush your enemies) '''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html Puck, Mac and Mobile.]'''\n\n'''Rate:'''\n\nComplete competitive cooperation and matchmaking. Depending on your final location in each game, go up the ladder or fall, from Iron to Challenger.\n\n==== '''One-day competition:''' ====\nEverything is open from a start-up to a full stop for you to succeed.\n\n==== [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html Style On Home:] ====\nIntroduce yourself to Little Legend through dance, emotion, and generally splash. Discover new little legends by playing TFT or buying them at the TFT Store.\n\n==== '''Battel It out:''' ====\nOffices Your Opponents Be Emerging A Team With League Of Legends Champions Who Fight Your Own.\n\n==== [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html Rank:] ====\nFull Compatibility Support & Meeting. From Iron to Challenger, Timberwolf was the Ladder in Your Final Standing in Every Game.\n\n==== '''Looking Good:''' ====\n\n==== [https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html Little Ligands Will Be Your Avatar, Dancing, Emoting, Animating and Generally Shong Wolf.] ====\n\n=== Details: ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+\n| colspan=\"2\" |\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Some Important Detail About This App\n|-\n|Latest Version\n|<nowiki>War Strategy Game. Play Online | MMO Warfare Game | Vikings\u2122\u200e</nowiki>\n|-\n|Requirements\n|Windows 7, Windows 2008, Windows 8, Windows 10, Windows 2000, Windows XP, Windows 98, Windows 2003, Windows Vista, Windows 2012 & Android Mobiles\n|-\n|File Size\n|46.9MBs\n|-\n|Author/Product\n|Riot Games, Inc\n|-\n|New Update\n|4April 2020.\n|-\n|'''''Note''[https://brandsofttech.blogspot.com/2020/04/war-strategy-game-play-online-mmo.html Team Fight Strategy: A Statement of the League of Legends Strategy Game:]'''\n|Latest Software, Apps & \u00a0Games are Available '''''\u201dClick Here\u201d'''''\n|}\n{{Software digital distribution platforms}}\n\n[[Category:Brands that became generic]]\n[[Category:Software distribution platforms]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Digital distribution platform for application softwares}}\n{{pp-pc1|expiry=July 30, 2020}}\n{{About|the concept|the store for Apple iOS apps|App Store (iOS)|the store for Apple Mac apps|App Store (macOS)}}\nAn '''app store''' (or '''app marketplace''') is a type of [[digital distribution]] platform for computer software called [[Application software|Applications]], often in a mobile context. Apps provide a specific set of functions which, by definition, do not include the running of the computer itself. Complex software designed for use on a [[personal computer]], for example, may have a related app designed for use on a [[mobile device]]. Today apps are normally designed to run on a specific [[operating system]]\u2014such as the contemporary [[iOS]], [[macOS]], [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] or [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\u2014but in the past [[mobile carrier]]s had their own portals for apps and related media content.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.telecomcircle.com/2009/05/the-economics-of-mobile-application-stores/ | title=The Economics of Mobile Application Store| date=2009-05-17}}</ref>\n\n== Basic concept ==\nAn app store is any digital storefront intended to allow search and review of software titles or other media offered for sale electronically. Critically, the application storefront itself provides a secure, uniform experience that automates the electronic purchase, decryption and installation of software applications or other digital media. \n\nApp stores typically organize the apps they offer based on: the function(s) provided by the app (including games, multimedia or productivity), the device for which the app was designed, and the operating system on which the app will run.\n\nApp stores typically take the form of an [[Online shopping|online store]], where [[End-user|users]] can browse through these different app categories, view information about each app (such as reviews or ratings), and acquire the app (including app purchase, if necessary \u2013 many apps are offered at no cost). The selected app is offered as an automatic download, after which the app installs. Some app stores may also include a system to [[kill switch|automatically remove an installed program]] from devices under certain conditions, with the goal of protecting the user against malicious software.<ref name=cw-remotedisable>{{cite web|title=Microsoft: We can remotely delete Windows 8 apps|url=http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/9222518/Microsoft_We_can_remotely_delete_Windows_8_apps |work=[[Computerworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] |accessdate=8 October 2013|date=2011-12-08 }}</ref>\n\nApp stores typically provide a way for users to give reviews and ratings. Those reviews are useful for other users, for developers and for app store owners. Users can select the best apps based on ratings, developers get feedback on what features are praised or disliked and finally, app store owners can detect bad apps and malicious developers by automatically analyzing the reviews with data mining techniques.<ref>{{Cite book  |doi=10.1109/MobileSoft.2015.8|isbn=978-0-7695-5566-9|chapter=A Recommender System of Buggy App Checkers for App Store Moderators|title=2015 2nd ACM International Conference on Mobile Software Engineering and Systems|pages=1\u201311|year=2015|last1=Gomez|first1=Maria|last2=Rouvoy|first2=Romain|last3=Monperrus|first3=Martin|last4=Seinturier|first4=Lionel|chapter-url=https://hal.inria.fr/hal-01079681/file/RR_BuggyAppCheckers-v2.pdf}}</ref>\n\nMany app stores are [[curator|curated]] by their owners, requiring that submissions of prospective apps go through an approval process. These apps are inspected for compliance with certain guidelines (such as those for [[quality control]] and [[censorship]]), including the requirement that a [[Commission (remuneration)|commission]] be collected on each sale of a paid app. Some app stores provides feedback to developers: number of installations, issues in the field (latency, crash, etc.).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gomez |first1=Maria |last2=Adams |first2=Bram |last3=Maalej |first3=Walid |last4=Monperrus |first4=Martin |last5=Rouvoy |first5=Romain |title=App Store 2.0: From Crowdsourced Information to Actionable Feedback in Mobile Ecosystems |journal=IEEE Software |date=March 2017 |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=81\u201389 |doi=10.1109/ms.2017.46 |url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01406422/document|arxiv=1807.00518 }}</ref>\n\nResearchers have proposed new features for app stores. For instance, the app store can deliver a unique [[software diversity|diversified version]] of the app for sake of security.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Franz |first1=Michael |title=E unibus pluram: massive-scale software diversity as a defense mechanism |date=21 September 2010 |pages=7\u201316 |doi=10.1145/1900546.1900550 | publisher=ACM}}</ref> The app store can also orchestrate monitoring and bug fixing to detect and repair crashes in applications.<ref>{{cite book |doi=10.1109/icse.2015.195 |chapter-url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01105173/document|isbn=978-1-4799-1934-5 |chapter=When App Stores Listen to the Crowd to Fight Bugs in the Wild|title=2015 IEEE/ACM 37th IEEE International Conference on Software Engineering|pages=567\u2013570|year=2015|last1=Gomez|first1=Maria|last2=Martineza|first2=Matias|last3=Monperrus|first3=Martin|last4=Rouvoy|first4=Romain|url=https://hal.inria.fr/hal-01105173/file/NIER15-preprint.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Precursors===\nThe [[Electronic AppWrapper]]<ref name=\"CT-AW3\">[http://www.kevra.org/TheBestOfNext/SWCatalogs/page274/page274.html Electronic AppWrapper]. Kevra.org. Retrieved on 2013-11-22.</ref> was the first commercial electronic software distribution catalog to collectively manage encryption and provide digital rights for apps and digital media<ref name=PR-AW3>[https://groups.google.com/group/comp.sys.next.announce/msg/56aacf1318e577ce  AppWrapper Volume1 Issue 3 Ships]. Groups.google.com. Retrieved on 2013-11-22.</ref> (issue #3 was the app store originally demonstrated to Steve Jobs at NeXTWorld EXPO).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carey|first1=Richard|title=Electronic Recollections, By Ricard Carey|url=http://appstorey.com/2015/07/17/electronic-recollections-by-ricard-carey/|website=AppStorey|publisher=Richard Carey|date=2015-07-17}}</ref> While a Senior Editor at [[NeXTWORLD Magazine]], [[Simson Garfinkel]], rated The [[Electronic AppWrapper]] 4 3/4 Cubes (out of 5), in his formal review. Paget's [[Electronic AppWrapper]] was named a finalist in the highly  competitive InVision Multimedia '93 awards in January, 1993 and won the Best of Breed award for Content and Information at NeXTWORLD Expo in May, 1993.<ref name=NW-AW3>Ruby, Dan (August 1993) [http://www.blackholeinc.com/Library/93%20Aug.html Our First Annual Awards for NEXTSTEP Product Excellence]. NeXTWORLD.</ref>\n[[File:The Electronic AppWrapper 3D Reality Screen Shot.png|thumb|A Screen Shot of Stone Design's 3DReality running on the Electronic AppWrapper, the first app store]]\nPrior to the Electronic AppWrapper which first shipped in 1992 people were used to software distributed via floppy disks or CD-ROMs, one could even download software using a web browser or command-line tools. Many [[Linux]] [[Linux distribution|distributions]] and other [[Unix-like]] systems provide a tool known as a [[package management system|package manager]], which allows a user to automatically manage the software installed on their systems (including both operating system components and third-party software) using [[command line]] tools{{emdash}}new software (and the packages required for its proper operation) can be retrieved from local or remote [[Web mirror|mirrors]] and automatically installed in a single process. Notable package managers in Unix-like operating systems have included [[FreeBSD Ports]] (1994), [[pkgsrc]] (1997), [[Debian]]'s [[Advanced Packaging Tool|APT]] (1998), [[Yellowdog Updater, Modified|YUM]], and [[Gentoo Linux|Gentoo]]'s [[Portage (software)|Portage]] (which unlike most package managers, distributes packages containing [[source code]] that is automatically [[compiler|compiled]] instead of [[executable]]s). Some package managers have [[graphical user interface|graphical]] front-end software which can be used to browse available packages and perform operations, such as [[Synaptic (software)|Synaptic]] (which is often used as a front-end for APT).\n\nIn 1996, the SUSE Linux distribution has [[YaST]] as frontend for its own app repository. Mandriva Linux has [[urpmi]] with GUI frontend called [[Rpmdrake]]. Fedora and [[Red Hat Enterprise Linux]] has [[Yellowdog Updater, Modified|YUM]] in 2003 as a successor of YUP (developed at [[Duke University]] for [[Red Hat Linux]]).\n\nIn 1997, BeDepot a third-party app store and package manager ([[Software Valet]]) for [[BeOS]] was launched, which operated until 2001. It was eventually acquired by Be Inc. BeDepot allowed for both commercial and free apps as well as handling updates\n\nIn 1998, Information Technologies India Ltd (ITIL) launched Palmix, a web based app store exclusively for mobile and handheld devices. Palmix sold apps for the three major PDA platforms of the time: the Palm OS based Palm Pilots, Windows CE based devices, and Psion Epoc handhelds.<ref name=Palmix>{{cite web|title=A one stop shop for so-oft-ware for Palmtops and Handhelds |url=http://www.palmix.itil.com/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000818162218/http://www.palmix.itil.com/ |archivedate=August 18, 2000 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, [[NTT DoCoMo]] launched [[i-mode]], the first integrated online app store for mobile phones, gaining nationwide popularity in [[Japanese mobile phone culture]]. DoCoMo used a revenue-sharing business model, allowing content creators and app providers to keep up to 91% of revenue.<ref>Mary J. Cronin (2010), [https://books.google.com/books?id=70m6XdOtnG0C&pg=PA135 ''Smart Products, Smarter Services: Strategies for Embedded Control'', p. 135], [[Cambridge University Press]]</ref> Other operators outside Japan also made their own portals after this, such as [[Vodafone live!]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/vodafone-calls-mobiles-go-live/508233 |title = Vodafone calls on mobiles to go Live!}}</ref> At this time mobile phone manufacturer [[Nokia]] also introduced carrier-free downloadable content with [[Club Nokia]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB99055184153156198 | title='Club Nokia' Service Could Put Firm in Awkward Position with Operators| newspaper=Wall Street Journal| date=2001-05-23| last1=Newswires| first1=Buster Kantrowdow Jones}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2001, [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint PCS]] launched the Ringers & More Wireless Download Service for their then-new 3G wireless network. This allowed subscribers to the Sprint PCS mobile phone network to download ringtones, wallpaper, J2ME applications and later full music tracks to certain phones. The user interface worked through a web browser on the desktop computer, and a version was available through the handset.<ref name=sprintpcs>{{cite web|title=PRS Newswire: Sprint Customers Will Soon Personalize their Wireless Phones with New Sprint PCS Ringers & More(SM) Wireless Download Service|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sprint-customers-will-soon-personalize-their-wireless-phones-with-new-sprint-pcs-ringers--moresm-wireless-download-service-74513067.html|accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the commercial Linux distribution [[Linspire]] (then known as LindowsOS{{emdash}}which was founded by [[Michael Robertson (businessman)|Michael Robertson]], founder of [[MP3.com]]) introduced an app store known as [[CNR (software)|Click'N'Run]] (CNR). For an annual subscription fee, users could perform one-click installation of free and paid apps through the CNR software. [[Doc Searls]] believed that the ease-of-use of CNR could help make [[desktop Linux]] a feasible reality.<ref name=lm-cnr>{{cite magazine|title=Click-N-Run: an Easier Future for Customers?|url=http://www.linuxjournal.com/article/6718|magazine=Linux Journal|accessdate=13 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 [[Handango]] introduced the first on-device app store for finding, installing and buying software for smartphones. App download and purchasing are completed directly on the device so sync with a computer is not necessary. Description, rating and screenshot are available for any app.\n\nIn 2005 [[Nokia 770 Internet Tablet]] has graphical frontend for its app repository to easily install app (its [[Maemo]] was based on [[Debian]]). Later Nokia also introduced [[Nokia Catalogs]], later known as Nokia Download!, for [[Symbian]] smartphones which had access to downloadable apps\u2014originally via third-parties like Handango or [[Jamba!]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://darlamack.blogs.com/darlamack/2005/12/nokia_catalog_a.html |title = Nokia S60 News and Reviews}}</ref> but from mid-2006 Nokia were offering their own content via the Nokia Content Discoverer.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.geoconnexion.com/news/nokia-content-discoverer |title = Nokia Content Discoverer &#124;\u00a0GeoConnexion}}</ref>\n\nThe popular Linux distribution [[Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu]] (also based on Debian) introduced its own graphical software manager known as the [[Ubuntu Software Center]] on version 9.10 as a replacement for Synaptic.<ref name=itpro-karmic>{{cite web|title=Ubuntu 9.10 review: Karmic Koala|url=http://www.itpro.co.uk/617119/ubuntu-910-review-karmic-koala/page/0/1|publisher=ITPro.com|accessdate=15 February 2013}}</ref>  On Ubuntu 10.10, released in October 2010, the Software Center expanded beyond only offering existing software from its repositories by adding the ability to purchase certain apps (which, at launch, was limited to [[Fluendo]]'s licensed [[DVD]] [[codec]]s).<ref name=ubuntu-1010apps>{{cite web|title=Review: Ubuntu 10.10 builds on app store, cloud service strengths|url=http://www.desktoplinux.com/news/NS2360404946.html|publisher=DesktopLinux.com|accessdate=15 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] released [[iOS|iPhone OS]] 2.0 in July 2008 for the [[iPhone]], together with the [[iOS App Store|App Store]], officially introducing third-party app development and distribution to the platform. The service allows users to purchase and download new apps for their device through either the App Store on the device, or through the [[iTunes Store]] on the [[iTunes]] desktop software.<ref name=pcw-appstorefuture>{{cite magazine|title=What the App Store Future Means for Developers and Users|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/227961/what_app_store_future_means_for_developers_and_users.html|magazine=PC World|date=May 16, 2011|author=Beckman, Mel }}</ref><ref name=wsj-breaking>{{cite news|title=Breaking Apple's Grip on the iPhone|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123629876097346481|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=March 6, 2009|author=Yukari Iwatani Kane}}</ref> While Apple has been criticized by some for how it operates the App Store, it has been a major financial success for the company.<ref name=\"40bill\">{{cite web|publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|title=App Store Tops 40 Billion Downloads with Almost Half in 2012|url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2013/01/07App-Store-Tops-40-Billion-Downloads-with-Almost-Half-in-2012.html|date=2013-01-07}}</ref> The popularity of Apple's App Store led to the rise of the generic term \"app store\", as well as the introduction of [[List of mobile software distribution platforms|equivalent marketplaces]] by competing mobile operating systems: the [[Google Play|Android Market]] (later renamed to Google Play) launched alongside the release of the first [[Android (operating system)|Android]] smartphone (the [[HTC Dream]]) in September 2008,<ref name=cnet-androidlaunch>{{cite web|title=Hype builds for Android phone launch|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-10042908-94.html|website=CNET|date= September 16, 2008|author=Reardon, Marguerite }}</ref> [[BlackBerry]]'s [[BlackBerry World|App World]] launched in April 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-17938_105-10188400-1.html?tag=mncol;txt |title=RIM store crowned BlackBerry App World |author=Cha, Bonnie |publisher=CNET News |date=2009-03-04 |accessdate=2009-03-09}}</ref><ref name=pcw-ios2>{{cite magazine|title=Apple Releases iPhone OS 2.0 Update|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/148247/iphone_2.html|magazine=PC World|accessdate=13 February 2013|date=2008-07-11}}</ref> as well as [[Nokia]]'s [[Ovi Store]] and [[Microsoft]]'s [[Windows Marketplace for Mobile]] both launching that year too.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.mobilefun.co.uk/blog/2009/05/nokia-ovi-store-now-available/ |title = Nokia Ovi Store now available|date = 2009-05-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/microsoft-opens-windows-marketplace-for-mobile-with-246-apps/ |title = Microsoft opens Windows Marketplace for Mobile with 246 apps}}</ref>\n\n==\"App Store\" trademark==\n{{See also|Apple Inc. litigation#Amazon \"App Store\"}}\n\nDue to its popularity, the term \"app store\" (first used by the [[Electronic AppWrapper]]<ref name=\"CT-AW3\" /> and later popularized by [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s [[iOS App Store|App Store]] for [[iOS]] devices) has frequently been used as a [[generic trademark]] to refer to other distribution platforms of a similar nature. Apple asserted [[trademark]] claims over the phrase, and filed a trademark registration for \"App Store\" in 2008. In 2011, Apple [[Apple Inc. litigation#Amazon \"App Store\"|sued]] both [[Amazon (company)|Amazon.com]] (which runs the [[Amazon Appstore]] for Android-based devices) and [[GetJar]] (who has offered its services since 2004) for [[trademark infringement]] and [[false advertising]] regarding the use of the term \"app store\" to refer to their services.<ref name=bgr-getjar>{{cite web|title=GetJar responds to Apple's cease-and-desist letter over 'App Store' name|url=http://bgr.com/2011/07/11/getjar-responds-to-apples-cease-and-desist-letter-over-app-store-name/|publisher=BGR|accessdate=13 February 2013|date=2011-07-11}}</ref> [[Microsoft]] filed multiple objections against Apple's attempt to register the name as a trademark, considering it to already be a generic term.<ref name=pcmag-msappstore>{{cite magazine|title=Microsoft Files Another Objection in Apple's 'App Store' Trademark Case|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2382855,00.asp|magazine=PC Magazine|date= March 30, 2011|author=Yin, Sara }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Apple's claims were rejected by a US District judge, who argued that the company presented no evidence that Amazon had \"[attempted] to mimic Apple's site or advertising\", or communicated that its service \"possesses the characteristics and qualities that the public has come to expect from the Apple APP STORE and/or Apple products\"<ref name=ars-rejected>{{cite web|title=No app for that: Apple's false ad suit over Amazon Appstore thrown out|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/01/no-app-for-that-apples-false-ad-suit-over-amazon-appstore-thrown-out/|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> In July 2013, Apple dropped its case.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bostic |first=Kevin |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/13/07/09/apple-drops-app-store-lawsuit-against-amazon-says-no-need-to-pursue-case |title=Apple drops 'App Store' lawsuit against Amazon, says no need to pursue case |publisher=Appleinsider.com |date=2013-07-09 |accessdate=2014-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Electronic commerce]]\n* [[Digital distribution in video games]]\n* [[Comparison of mobile operating systems]]\n* [[App store optimization]]\n* [[List of Android app stores]]\n* [[List of mobile software distribution platforms]]\n** [[App Store (iOS)]], [[iOS app approvals]], [[App Store (watchOS)]], [[App Store (iMessage)]]\n** [[Google Play]]\n** [[Microsoft Store (digital)]]\n* Desktop software distribution platforms\n** [[AppStream]]\n** [[Chrome Web Store]]\n** [[App Store (macOS)]], [[App Store (tvOS)]]\n** [[Microsoft Store (digital)]]\n** [[Setapp]]\n** [[Steam (software)|Steam]]\n** [[Ubuntu Software Center]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n{{Software digital distribution platforms}}\n\n[[Category:Brands that became generic]]\n[[Category:Software distribution platforms]]\n", "name_user": "BrandNew Software and Apps & games", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBasic concept", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/App_store"}
{"title_page": "Julian Knight (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = Julian Knight\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|image = Official portrait of Julian Knight MP crop 2.jpg\n| office1          = Chair of the [[Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Damian Collins]]\n| successor1       = \n| term_start1      = 29 January 2020\n| term_end1        = \n|office2           = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Solihull (UK Parliament constituency)|Solihull]]\n|term_start2       = 7 May 2015\n|term_end2         = \n|predecessor2      = [[Lorely Burt]]\n|successor2        = \n|majority2         = 21,273 (38.4%)\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1972|1|5|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Chester]], [[England]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|spouse           = Philippa Harrison\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Hull]]\n|religion         = [[Christianity]]\n|website          = {{url|www.julianknight.org.uk|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Julian Carlton Knight'''<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61961 |date=19 June 2017 |page=11779}}</ref> (born 5 January 1972) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician. He was elected as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Solihull (UK Parliament constituency)|Solihull]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000931 | title= Solihull Parliamentary constituency | publisher=BBC | accessdate=9 May 2015| work= BBC News }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nKnight was born in 1972 in [[Chester]], and grew up in a lone parent family.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last1=Knight|first1=Julian|title=About|url=http://www.julianknight.org.uk/about-julian|website=Julian Knight|accessdate=20 September 2015}}</ref> He attended [[Chester Catholic High School]], and went on to study History at the [[University of Hull]], the first in his family to do so.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Employment before Parliament==\n\nAfter graduating with a 2:2, Knight moved to London to find work, doing a variety of jobs before finding a job on a local newspaper. He moved up in journalism over the intervening years, working for the [[BBC]] as personal finance and consumer affairs reporter for five years until 2007, working across online, TV and radio. In 2007 he became the Money and Property Editor of ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/biography/julian-knight-8192501.html | title= Julian Knight - The Independent on Sunday | publisher=Independent | accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Knight was criticised for a book he authored on [[Tax avoidance|tax avoidance]]. In his 2004 book, 'Wills, Probate and Inheritance Tax for Dummies', Knight \"sets out ways that hardworking parents can pass on the graft of a lifetime\" to their children. In the book, he is critical of the system of [[Inheritance Tax]] that existed at the point of publishing. He distinguished between personal tax avoidance, which he advised families on, and the \"aggressive tax avoidance\" of some multinational companies.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/23/tory-candidate-julian-knight-solihull-criticised-book-tax-avoidance | title= Tory candidate for Solihull under fire over book on tax avoidance | publisher=Guardian | accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Elections===\nIn 2014, Knight was selected to be the Conservative candidate for [[Solihull (UK Parliament constituency)|Solihull,]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.solihullboroughconservatives.org.uk/news/solihull-conservatives-select-julian-knight-our-candidate|title=Solihull Conservatives select Julian Knight as our Parliamentary Candidate|website=Solihull Borough|language=en|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westmidlandsconservatives.com/news/julian-knight-selected-solihull-0|title=Julian Knight selected for Solihull|website=West Midlands|language=en|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref> a former Conservative safe seat which had been won by the Liberal Democrats in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/find-information-by-subject/elections-and-referendums/past-elections-and-referendums/uk-general-elections/2005-uk-general-election-results/solihull|title=Electoral Commission {{!}} Solihull|website=www.electoralcommission.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/lib-dems-hold-inquest-after-their-decapitation-strategy-misses-targets-220427.html|title=Lib Dems hold inquest after their 'decapitation strategy' misses|work=The Independent|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> At the  [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] Knight won the seat back for the Conservatives with a majority of 12,902, after an 11.9 per cent swing towards the Conservatives.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000931|title=Solihull parliamentary constituency - Election 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the 2016 referendum on the UK\u2019s membership within the European Union, Knight campaigned to remain but now backs the Conservative Party policy of exiting the EU.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/solihulls-conservative-mp-julian-knight-will-vote-stay-europe/|title=Solihull's Conservative MP Julian Knight will vote to stay in Europe|work=Solihull Observer|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nKnight defended his seat at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] and was returned with an increased majority.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000931|title=Solihull parliamentary constituency - Election 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nKnight once again defended his seat during the 2019 General Election. He once again increased his majority, this time to 21,273. <ref> https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000931 </ref> The Liberal Democrats were again pushed into third place by Labour. <ref> https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/general-election-2019-solihull-result-17326399.amp </ref>\n\n===Government===\nIn January 2018, Knight was appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] at the Ministry of Justice<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2018/01/list-of-ppss.html|title=List of PPS's {{!}} Conservative Home|work=Conservative Home|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> providing support to Ministers. In September 2018 he moved to the Department for Work and Pensions before moving to HM Treasury in January 2019.\n\nKnight is a passionate animal rights advocate and called for CCTV in slaughter houses before it was Government policy.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.julianknight.org.uk/news/knight-hails-governments-progress-animal-welfare |title = Knight hails Government's progress on animal welfare}}</ref>\n\nKnight also serves as the [[Prime Ministerial Trade Envoy]] to [[Mongolia]], where he forms part of a network of parliamentarians with the role to strengthen relations with foreign countries, and aide British businesses in accessing foreign markets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/trade-envoys|title=Trade envoys|work=GOV.UK|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en}}</ref> In April 2018, Knight made his first visit to the country as Trade Envoy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://president.mn/en/2018/04/06/president-receives-uk-trade-envoy-julian-knight/|title=PRESIDENT RECEIVES UK TRADE ENVOY JULIAN KNIGHT - President of Mongolia|date=6 April 2018|work=President of Mongolia|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> Knight is due to make his second visit in September 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thecea.org.uk/trade-mission-mongolia-16th-21st-september-2018/|title=Trade Mission to Mongolia 16th \u2013 21st September 2018 - CEA: Construction Equipment Association|date=15 August 2018|work=CEA: Construction Equipment Association|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Committees===\nFrom July 2015 to April 2017, Knight served as a member of the House of Commons [[Communities and Local Government Committee]],<ref name=\"Julian Knight MP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/julian-knight/4410|title=Julian Knight MP|website=UK Parliament|language=en|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref> during which time he co-sponsored the Government\u2019s [[Homelessness Reduction Bill 2016\u201317|Homelessness Reduction Act 2017]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/solihull-mp-julian-knight-has-pledged-to-support-solihull-council-in-its-new-effort-to-tackle-homelessness-in-the-borough/|title=Solihull MP Julian Knight has pledged to support Solihull Council in its new effort to tackle homelessness in the borough|work=Solihull Observer|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nSince December 2016 he has served on the [[Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee|Culture, Media, and Sport Committee]], later the [[Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee]].<ref name=\"Julian Knight MP\"/> In that role he has made several high-profile interventions, including on the BBC gender pay row<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/02/01/sarah-montague-gobsmacked-bbc-gender-pay-report/|title=Sarah Montague: I was gobsmacked by BBC gender pay report|last=Singh|first=Anita|date=1 February 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/31/world/europe/bbc-gender-pay-carrie-gracie.html|title=BBC Managers Face Barrage of Criticism in Gender Pay Dispute|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en}}</ref> and against Facebook and disgraced digital company Cambridge Analytica during the Committee\u2019s inquiry into 'fake news'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/apr/26/facebook-morality-free-zone-executive-mps-cambridge-analytica|title='Facebook is a morality-free zone': tech chief lambasted by MP|last=Waterson|first=Jim|date=26 April 2018|work=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/facebook-mp-parliament-hearing-cambridge-analytica-mike-schroepfer-mark-zuckerberg-a8323926.html|title=MPs laugh at Facebook boss during intense grilling in parliament|work=The Independent|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 Knight was elected as Chair of the Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Select Committee. Knight beat incumbent Chair, Damian Collins, by 9 votes to win the Committee. <ref> https://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2020/january/select-committee-chair-election-nominations-2020/commons-committee-chair-elections-2020/ </ref> In the election he pledged to \u201cget the BBC sorted, get broadband sorted, and get progress in sport sorted.\u201d <ref> https://order-order.com/2020/02/03/knight-plans-bbc-battle/ </ref>\n\n== Other work ==\n\nKnight has written books on a variety of subjects for the [[For Dummies|For Dummies series]], including the [[European debt crisis|Euro crisis]], Retiring Wealthy and The Royal Wedding.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who is Julian Knight|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/who-julian-knight---five-9212326|website=Birmingham Mail|accessdate=20 September 2015|date=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nKnight lives in [[Solihull]]. He is married to Philippa, a former nurse.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=julian-knight/4410 |publicwhip=Julian_Knight |theywork=julian_knight}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lorely Burt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Solihull (UK Parliament constituency)|Solihull]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{West Midlands Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knight, Julian}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:British journalists]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Independent people]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = Julian Knight\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|image = Official portrait of Julian Knight MP crop 2.jpg\n| office1          = Chair of the [[Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Damian Collins]]\n| successor1       = \n| term_start1      = 29 January 2020\n| term_end1        = \n|office2           = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Solihull (UK Parliament constituency)|Solihull]]\n|term_start2       = 7 May 2015\n|term_end2         = \n|predecessor2      = [[Lorely Burt]]\n|successor2        = \n|majority2         = 21,273 (38.4%)\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1972|1|5|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Chester]], [[England]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|spouse           = Philippa Harrison\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Hull]]\n|religion         = [[Christianity]]\n|website          = {{url|www.julianknight.org.uk|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Julian Carlton Knight'''<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61961 |date=19 June 2017 |page=11779}}</ref> (born 5 January 1972) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician. He was elected as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Solihull (UK Parliament constituency)|Solihull]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000931 | title= Solihull Parliamentary constituency | publisher=BBC | accessdate=9 May 2015| work= BBC News }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nKnight was born in 1972 in [[Chester]], and grew up in a lone parent family.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last1=Knight|first1=Julian|title=About|url=http://www.julianknight.org.uk/about-julian|website=Julian Knight|accessdate=20 September 2015}}</ref> He attended [[Chester Catholic High School]], and went on to study History at the [[University of Hull]], the first in his family to do so.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Employment before Parliament==\n\nAfter graduating with a 2:2, Knight moved to London to find work, doing a variety of jobs before finding a job on a local newspaper. He moved up in journalism over the intervening years, working for the [[BBC]] as personal finance and consumer affairs reporter for five years until 2007, working across online, TV and radio. In 2007 he became the Money and Property Editor of ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/biography/julian-knight-8192501.html | title= Julian Knight - The Independent on Sunday | publisher=Independent | accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Knight was criticised for a book he authored on [[Tax Avoidance|tax avoidance]]. In his 2004 book, 'Wills, Probate and Inheritance Tax for Dummies', Knight \"sets out ways that hardworking parents can pass on the graft of a lifetime\" onto their children. In the book, he is critical of the system of [[Inheritance Tax]] that existed at the point of publishing. He distinguished between personal tax avoidance, which he advised families on, and the \"aggressive tax avoidance\" of some multinational companies.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/23/tory-candidate-julian-knight-solihull-criticised-book-tax-avoidance | title= Tory candidate for Solihull under fire over book on tax avoidance | publisher=Guardian | accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Elections===\nIn 2014, Knight was selected to be the Conservative candidate for [[Solihull (UK Parliament constituency)|Solihull,]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.solihullboroughconservatives.org.uk/news/solihull-conservatives-select-julian-knight-our-candidate|title=Solihull Conservatives select Julian Knight as our Parliamentary Candidate|website=Solihull Borough|language=en|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westmidlandsconservatives.com/news/julian-knight-selected-solihull-0|title=Julian Knight selected for Solihull|website=West Midlands|language=en|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref> a former Conservative safe seat which had been won by the Liberal Democrats in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/find-information-by-subject/elections-and-referendums/past-elections-and-referendums/uk-general-elections/2005-uk-general-election-results/solihull|title=Electoral Commission {{!}} Solihull|website=www.electoralcommission.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/lib-dems-hold-inquest-after-their-decapitation-strategy-misses-targets-220427.html|title=Lib Dems hold inquest after their 'decapitation strategy' misses|work=The Independent|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> At the  [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] Knight won the seat back for the Conservatives with a majority of 12,902, after an 11.9 per cent swing towards the Conservatives.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000931|title=Solihull parliamentary constituency - Election 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the 2016 referendum on the UK\u2019s membership within the European Union, Knight campaigned to remain but now backs the Conservative Party policy of exiting the EU.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/solihulls-conservative-mp-julian-knight-will-vote-stay-europe/|title=Solihull's Conservative MP Julian Knight will vote to stay in Europe|work=Solihull Observer|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nKnight defended his seat at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] and was returned with an increased majority.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000931|title=Solihull parliamentary constituency - Election 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nKnight once again defended his seat during the 2019 General Election. He once again increased his majority, this time to 21,273. <ref> https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000931 </ref> The Liberal Democrats were again pushed into third place by Labour. <ref> https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/general-election-2019-solihull-result-17326399.amp </ref>\n\n===Government===\nIn January 2018, Knight was appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] at the Ministry of Justice<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2018/01/list-of-ppss.html|title=List of PPS's {{!}} Conservative Home|work=Conservative Home|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> providing support to Ministers. In September 2018 he moved to the Department for Work and Pensions before moving to HM Treasury in January 2019.\n\nKnight is a passionate animal rights advocate and called for CCTV in slaughter houses before it was Government policy.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.julianknight.org.uk/news/knight-hails-governments-progress-animal-welfare |title = Knight hails Government's progress on animal welfare}}</ref>\n\nKnight also serves as the [[Prime Ministerial Trade Envoy]] to [[Mongolia]], where he forms part of a network of parliamentarians with the role to strengthen relations with foreign countries, and aide British businesses in accessing foreign markets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/trade-envoys|title=Trade envoys|work=GOV.UK|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en}}</ref> In April 2018, Knight made his first visit to the country as Trade Envoy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://president.mn/en/2018/04/06/president-receives-uk-trade-envoy-julian-knight/|title=PRESIDENT RECEIVES UK TRADE ENVOY JULIAN KNIGHT - President of Mongolia|date=6 April 2018|work=President of Mongolia|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> Knight is due to make his second visit in September 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thecea.org.uk/trade-mission-mongolia-16th-21st-september-2018/|title=Trade Mission to Mongolia 16th \u2013 21st September 2018 - CEA: Construction Equipment Association|date=15 August 2018|work=CEA: Construction Equipment Association|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Committees===\nFrom July 2015 to April 2017, Knight served as a member of the House of Commons [[Communities and Local Government Committee]],<ref name=\"Julian Knight MP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/julian-knight/4410|title=Julian Knight MP|website=UK Parliament|language=en|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref> during which time he co-sponsored the Government\u2019s [[Homelessness Reduction Bill 2016\u201317|Homelessness Reduction Act 2017]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/solihull-mp-julian-knight-has-pledged-to-support-solihull-council-in-its-new-effort-to-tackle-homelessness-in-the-borough/|title=Solihull MP Julian Knight has pledged to support Solihull Council in its new effort to tackle homelessness in the borough|work=Solihull Observer|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nSince December 2016 he has served on the [[Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee|Culture, Media, and Sport Committee]], later the [[Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Committee]].<ref name=\"Julian Knight MP\"/> In that role he has made several high-profile interventions, including on the BBC gender pay row<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/02/01/sarah-montague-gobsmacked-bbc-gender-pay-report/|title=Sarah Montague: I was gobsmacked by BBC gender pay report|last=Singh|first=Anita|date=1 February 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/31/world/europe/bbc-gender-pay-carrie-gracie.html|title=BBC Managers Face Barrage of Criticism in Gender Pay Dispute|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en}}</ref> and against Facebook and disgraced digital company Cambridge Analytica during the Committee\u2019s inquiry into 'fake news'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/apr/26/facebook-morality-free-zone-executive-mps-cambridge-analytica|title='Facebook is a morality-free zone': tech chief lambasted by MP|last=Waterson|first=Jim|date=26 April 2018|work=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/facebook-mp-parliament-hearing-cambridge-analytica-mike-schroepfer-mark-zuckerberg-a8323926.html|title=MPs laugh at Facebook boss during intense grilling in parliament|work=The Independent|access-date=9 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 Knight was elected as Chair of the Digital, Culture, Media and Sport Select Committee. Knight beat incumbent Chair, Damian Collins, by 9 votes to win the Committee. <ref> https://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2020/january/select-committee-chair-election-nominations-2020/commons-committee-chair-elections-2020/ </ref> In the election he pledged to \u201cget the BBC sorted, get broadband sorted, and get progress in sport sorted.\u201d <ref> https://order-order.com/2020/02/03/knight-plans-bbc-battle/ </ref>\n\n== Other work ==\n\nKnight has written books on a variety of subjects for the [[For Dummies|For Dummies series]], including the [[European debt crisis|Euro crisis]], Retiring Wealthy and The Royal Wedding.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who is Julian Knight|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/who-julian-knight---five-9212326|website=Birmingham Mail|accessdate=20 September 2015|date=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nKnight lives in [[Solihull]]. He is married to Philippa, a former nurse.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=julian-knight/4410 |publicwhip=Julian_Knight |theywork=julian_knight}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lorely Burt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Solihull (UK Parliament constituency)|Solihull]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{West Midlands Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knight, Julian}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:British journalists]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Independent people]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "name_user": "Sjshart", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected ref to another page and piece of grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julian_Knight_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Francis Gofton", "text_new": "'''Sir Francis Gofton''' (died 1628) was an English courtier and administrator. He was an auditor of royal accounts and jewels, Chief Auditor of the Imprest from 1597 and Auditor of Mint from August 1603.<ref>''CSP Domestic, James I: 1603-1610'' (London, 1857), p. 33.</ref> Gofton acquired the manor of [[Heathrow (hamlet)|Heathrow]], and houses in [[Stockwell]] and [[West Ham]]. He was often called \"Auditor Gofton\".\n\n==Career==\nIn January 1603 the auditor Richard Sutton complained that he had been continually sick on a previous official visit to Ireland with Gofton and begged to be excused.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 12 (Hereford, 1910), p. 614.</ref>\n\nIn May 1603 he was asked with Sir [[Edward Coke]], Sir [[Thomas Gorges]], and Sir [[Thomas Knyvet, 1st Baron Knyvet|Thomas Knyvett]] to make an inventory of the jewels of [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth]] in the keeping of Mrs Mary Ratcliffe.<ref>Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Calendar State Papers James I: 1603-1610'' (London, 1857), pp. 10, 66 citing The National Archives TNA SP14/1/89 and SP14/6/9 (?Edward Carey).</ref>\n\nIn December 1603 he consulted with [[Thomas Sackville, 1st Earl of Dorset|Lord Buckhurst]], the [[Lord High Treasurer|Lord Treasurer]] at [[West Horsley Place]] over plans for the garrison at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]].<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 15 (London, 1930), p. 314.</ref> In January 1612 George Nicholson sent him accounts for Berwick noting that ten old pensioners and [[William Selby (died 1612)|Sir William Selby]] had died.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, James I: 1611-1618'' (London, 1858), p. 112.</ref>\n\nIn October 1604 he audited the accounts of Richard Mellersh, the former steward of the disgraced [[Henry Brooke, 11th Baron Cobham|Lord Cobham]] and [[Frances Howard, Countess of Kildare]].<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 16 (London, 1933), p. 331.</ref> He delivered Cobham's \"garter\" and \"George\" jewels to Sir Edward Carey, Master of the King's Jewels and Plate, in March 1605.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 17 (London, 1938), p. 96.</ref>\n\nHe made a list of 25 jewels which [[James VI and I|King James]] had given to [[Anne of Denmark]] from the crown jewels stored in the [[Tower of London]].<ref>Francis Palgrave, ''Antient Kalendars of the Exchequer'', vol. 3 (London, 1836), pp. 306-9 (not dated).</ref> In December 1604 he sent a list of jewels the king had given the queen to the [[Thomas Howard, 1st Earl of Suffolk|Earl of Suffolk]] and Viscount Cranborne.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 16 (London, 1933), pp. 385-6.</ref> He was owed \u00a3400 for a jewel given to [[Anne Livingstone, Countess of Eglinton]].<ref>The National Archives, TNA SP14/46/137.</ref>\n\nGofton had a house at [[West Ham]] on the outskirts of London where he had fishing rights, though he lodged in Red Cross street in the city. On 19 January 1606 a great porpoise was taken alive at West Ham, in a little Creek, a mile and a half within the land, and this was presented to Francis Gofton.<ref>Edmond Howes, ''The abridgement of the English Chronicle, first collected by M. Iohn Stow, and after him augmented with very many memorable antiquities, and continued with matters forreine and domesticall, vnto the beginning of the yeare, 1618. by E.H. Gentleman'' (London, 1618), p. 470.</ref> Gofton gave the porpoise to the [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Earl of Salisbury]].<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield: 1606'', vol. 18 (London, 1940), p. 26.</ref> This incident is often connected with a line in [[Ben Jonson]]'s play, ''[[Volpone]]''; \"Were there three porpoises seen above the Bridge, As they give out?\". [[Cecil House|Salisbury House]] being above [[London Bridge]] on the Thames.\n\nIn February 1608 the [[Privy Council of England]] sent him a letter reminding of him of a need for quality and curious workmanship in new plate delivered to the Jewel House to replace that given to ambassadors in September 1605.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield: 1608'', vol. 20 (London, 1968), p. 82.</ref>\n\nGofton sold lands and fishings on the [[River Erne|Erne]] in Ireland to [[Henry Folliott, 1st Baron Folliott|Sir Henry Folliot]] in April 1609, the former property of the Abbey of Assaroe near [[Ballyshannon]].<ref>James Morrin, ''Calendar of the patent and close rolls of chancery in Ireland'' (Dublin, 1863), pp. 388-9, 472: ''Calendar of the Patent Rolls of the Chancery of Ireland: James I'' pp. 128-9.</ref>\n\nHe was knighted in February 1619 with other commissioners for the royal household and navy. After the death of Anna of Denmark he and Sir Edward Coke inventoried her possessions at [[Somerset House|Denmark House]] and brought them to [[Greenwich Palace]].<ref>Norman MacClure, ''Letters of John Chamberlain'', vol. 2 (Philadelphia, 1939), pp. 210, 237.</ref>\n\nIn December 1621 his house at Stockwell, near the house of the ambassador Noel Caron, burnt down and all his stuff was lost.<ref>Norman MacClure, ''Letters of John Chamberlain'', vol. 2 (Philadelphia, 1939), p. 415.</ref> As owner of this property he was known as \"Francis Gofton of Stockwell\". In his will, written in 1626, Gofton mentions that he had spent considerable sums on the Stockwell house, which belonged to his wife, before and after the fire. By this time his London house was in St Giles without Cripplegate.<ref>The National Archives, TNA PROB 11/154/260.</ref> The lands at Stockwell manor had been bought by his wife's first husband, John Pyndar, in 1586.<ref>[https://www.british-history.ac.uk/survey-london/vol26/pp81-82  'Stockwell: Stockwell Manor', Survey of London: Volume 26, Lambeth: Southern Area, 1956.]</ref>\n\n==Jewels for the Spanish Match==\n0n 2 March 1623 King James wanted [[Edward Conway, 1st Viscount Conway|Secretary Conway]] to visit the Tower of London with [[Fulke Greville, 1st Baron Brooke|Lord Brooke]], the [[Thomas Edmondes|Treasurer of the Household]], the Chancellor of Exchequer, and [[George Heriot]] to select some \"fine jewels fit for a woman\", and others to be worn in hats. Some were for [[Charles I of England|Prince Charles]] to give as presents in Spain, others were intended to be returned. The selection was to be sent to the king at Newmarket.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic: 1618-1623'' (London, 1858), pp. 507, 520, 523, 528, 577.</ref> The jewels selected, including the king's hat badge of the letter \"I\" or \"J\" and others which had belonged to Anna of Denmark, were sent to Spain in March with [[Robert Carey, 1st Earl of Monmouth|Lord Carey of Leppington]] to [[Spencer Compton, 2nd Earl of Northampton|Lord Compton]], and in May with [[Francis Stuart (sailor)|Sir Francis Stewart]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic: 1618-1623'' (London, 1858), p. 520 citing TNA SP14/139/108 and p. 523 citing TNA SP14/139/63.</ref>\n\nGofton wrote to Secretary Conway about the plan of King Charles to sell jewels on 17 October 1625. He thought the best diamonds in the Tower of London had been sent to the king when he was at Canterbury and not returned, and the remainder in the Tower were \"verie meane\". He sent Conway an inventory including jewels returned from Spain, and contents of the \"chest of late Queen Anne\" which contained; a gold \"flagon\" bracelet; a jewel \"in fashion of a Jesus\" (the [[Christogram|cipher of Jesus, \"IHS\"]]); 41 small diamonds from a jewel in the shape of a bay leaf; an old cross set with six diamonds of an old cut with four rubies and pearls; a gold chain, buttons, and aglets of \"Spanish work\" filled with white [[ambergris]]; a bodkin set with a diamond cut like a heart; a great ruby set in claws of gold, and other jewels and stones.<ref>John Bruce,''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Charles I: 1625, 1626'' (London, 1858), p. 126 citing TNA SP16/7/120-124: Compare, Diana Scarisbrick, 'Anne of Denmark's Jewellery Inventory', ''Archaeologia'', 109 (1991), pp. 208, 214-5.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nFrancis Gofton died in 1628.\n\n==Personal life==\nFrancis Gofton married Katherine Kinsman (d. 1634), the widow of John Pynder (d. 1608), a vintner and Member of Parliament.<ref>[http://www.histparl.ac.uk/volume/1558-1603/member/pynder-john-1608 PYNDER, John (d.1608), of Cheapside, London, ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1558-1603'', ed. P.W. Hasler, 1981.]</ref> In her will, Katherine asked to be buried at the chapel of the [[Worshipful Company of Mercers|Mercers\u2019 Company]] near to John Pynder.<ref>The National Archives, TNA PROB 11/166/65, will of Katherine Gofton.</ref> Their children included:\n* Francis Gofton (d. 1642)\n* John Gofton (1615-1686). His mother left him a house called [[Down Hall, Barrow upon Humber|Downhall in Barrow]], Lincolnshire, and property in Stockwell including farms and the Old Orchard of the manor of Stockwell, with silver plate some formerly belonging to [[Roger Manners, 5th Earl of Rutland]].<ref>The National Archives, TNA PROB 11/166/65.</ref> He was buried at Lambeth.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gofton, Francis}}\n[[Category:1628 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:17th-century English people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sir Francis Gofton''' (died 1628) was an English courtier and administrator. He was an auditor of royal accounts and jewels, Chief Auditor of the Imprest from 1597 and Auditor of Mint from August 1603.<ref>''CSP Domestic, James I: 1603-1610'' (London, 1857), p. 33.</ref> Gofton acquired the manor of [[Heathrow (hamlet)|Heathrow]], and houses in [[Stockwell]] and [[West Ham]]. He was often called \"Auditor Gofton\".\n\n==Career==\nIn January 1603 the auditor Richard Sutton complained that he had been continually sick on a previous official visit to Ireland with Gofton and begged to be excused.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 12 (Hereford, 1910), p. 614.</ref>\n\nIn May 1603 he was asked with Sir [[Edward Coke]], Sir [[Thomas Gorges]], and Sir [[Thomas Knyvet, 1st Baron Knyvet|Thomas Knyvett]] to make an inventory of the jewels of [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth]] in the keeping of Mrs Mary Ratcliffe.<ref>Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Calendar State Papers James I: 1603-1610'' (London, 1857), pp. 10, 66 citing The National Archives TNA SP14/1/89 and SP14/6/9 (?Edward Carey).</ref>\n\nIn December 1603 he consulted with [[Thomas Sackville, 1st Earl of Dorset|Lord Buckhurst]], the [[Lord High Treasurer|Lord Treasurer]] at [[West Horsley Place]] over plans for the garrison at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]].<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 15 (London, 1930), p. 314.</ref> In January 1612 George Nicholson sent him accounts for Berwick noting that ten old pensioners and [[William Selby (died 1612)|Sir William Selby]] had died.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, James I: 1611-1618'' (London, 1858), p. 112.</ref>\n\nIn October 1604 he audited the accounts of Richard Mellersh, the former steward of the disgraced [[Henry Brooke, 11th Baron Cobham|Lord Cobham]] and [[Frances Howard, Countess of Kildare]].<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 16 (London, 1933), p. 331.</ref> He delivered Cobham's \"garter\" and \"George\" jewels to Sir Edward Carey, Master of the King's Jewels and Plate, in March 1605.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 17 (London, 1938), p. 96.</ref>\n\nHe made a list of 25 jewels which [[James VI and I|King James]] had given to [[Anne of Denmark]] from the crown jewels stored in the [[Tower of London]].<ref>Francis Palgrave, ''Antient Kalendars of the Exchequer'', vol. 3 (London, 1836), pp. 306-9 (not dated).</ref> In December 1604 he sent a list of jewels the king had given the queen to the [[Thomas Howard, 1st Earl of Suffolk|Earl of Suffolk]] and Viscount Cranborne.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 16 (London, 1933), pp. 385-6.</ref> He was owed \u00a3400 for a jewel given to [[Anne Livingstone, Countess of Eglinton]].<ref>The National Archives, TNA SP14/46/137.</ref>\n\nGofton had a house at [[West Ham]] on the outskirts of London where he had fishing rights, though he lodged in Red Cross street in the city. On 19 January 1606 a great porpoise was taken alive at West Ham, in a little Creek, a mile and a half within the land, and this was presented to Francis Gofton.<ref>Edmond Howes, ''The abridgement of the English Chronicle, first collected by M. Iohn Stow, and after him augmented with very many memorable antiquities, and continued with matters forreine and domesticall, vnto the beginning of the yeare, 1618. by E.H. Gentleman'' (London, 1618), p. 470.</ref> Gofton gave the porpoise to the [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Earl of Salisbury]].<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield: 1606'', vol. 18 (London, 1940), p. 26.</ref> This incident is often connected with a line in [[Ben Jonson]]'s play, ''[[Volpone]]''; \"Were there three porpoises seen above the Bridge, As they give out?\". [[Cecil House|Salisbury House]] being above [[London Bridge]] on the Thames.\n\nIn February 1608 the [[Privy Council of England]] sent him a letter reminding of him of a need for quality and curious workmanship in new plate delivered to the Jewel House to replace that given to ambassadors in September 1605.<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield: 1608'', vol. 20 (London, 1968), p. 82.</ref>\n\nGofton sold lands and fishings on the [[River Erne|Erne]] in Ireland to [[Henry Folliott, 1st Baron Folliott|Sir Henry Folliot]] in April 1609, the former property of the Abbey of Assaroe near [[Ballyshannon]].<ref>James Morrin, ''Calendar of the patent and close rolls of chancery in Ireland'' (Dublin, 1863), pp. 388-9, 472.</ref>\n\nHe was knighted in February 1619 with other commissioners for the royal household and navy. After the death of Anna of Denmark he and Sir Edward Coke inventoried her possessions at [[Somerset House|Denmark House]] and brought them to [[Greenwich Palace]].<ref>Norman MacClure, ''Letters of John Chamberlain'', vol. 2 (Philadelphia, 1939), pp. 210, 237.</ref>\n\nIn December 1621 his house at Stockwell, near the house of the ambassador Noel Caron, burnt down and all his stuff was lost.<ref>Norman MacClure, ''Letters of John Chamberlain'', vol. 2 (Philadelphia, 1939), p. 415.</ref> As owner of this property he was known as \"Francis Gofton of Stockwell\". In his will, written in 1626, Gofton mentions that he had spent considerable sums on the Stockwell house, which belonged to his wife, before and after the fire. By this time his London house was in St Giles without Cripplegate.<ref>The National Archives, TNA PROB 11/154/260.</ref> The lands at Stockwell manor had been bought by his wife's first husband, John Pyndar, in 1586.<ref>[https://www.british-history.ac.uk/survey-london/vol26/pp81-82  'Stockwell: Stockwell Manor', Survey of London: Volume 26, Lambeth: Southern Area, 1956.]</ref>\n\n==Jewels for the Spanish Match==\n0n 2 March 1623 King James wanted [[Edward Conway, 1st Viscount Conway|Secretary Conway]] to visit the Tower of London with [[Fulke Greville, 1st Baron Brooke|Lord Brooke]], the [[Thomas Edmondes|Treasurer of the Household]], the Chancellor of Exchequer, and [[George Heriot]] to select some \"fine jewels fit for a woman\", and others to be worn in hats. Some were for [[Charles I of England|Prince Charles]] to give as presents in Spain, others were intended to be returned. The selection was to be sent to the king at Newmarket.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic: 1618-1623'' (London, 1858), pp. 507, 520, 523, 528, 577.</ref> The jewels selected, including the king's hat badge of the letter \"I\" or \"J\" and others which had belonged to Anna of Denmark, were sent to Spain in March with [[Robert Carey, 1st Earl of Monmouth|Lord Carey of Leppington]] to [[Spencer Compton, 2nd Earl of Northampton|Lord Compton]], and in May with [[Francis Stuart (sailor)|Sir Francis Stewart]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic: 1618-1623'' (London, 1858), p. 520 citing TNA SP14/139/108 and p. 523 citing TNA SP14/139/63.</ref>\n\nGofton wrote to Secretary Conway about the plan of King Charles to sell jewels on 17 October 1625. He thought the best diamonds in the Tower of London had been sent to the king when he was at Canterbury and not returned, and the remainder in the Tower were \"verie meane\". He sent Conway an inventory including jewels returned from Spain, and contents of the \"chest of late Queen Anne\" which contained; a gold \"flagon\" bracelet; a jewel \"in fashion of a Jesus\" (the [[Christogram|cipher of Jesus, \"IHS\"]]); 41 small diamonds from a jewel in the shape of a bay leaf; an old cross set with six diamonds of an old cut with four rubies and pearls; a gold chain, buttons, and aglets of \"Spanish work\" filled with white [[ambergris]]; a bodkin set with a diamond cut like a heart; a great ruby set in claws of gold, and other jewels and stones.<ref>John Bruce,''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Charles I: 1625, 1626'' (London, 1858), p. 126 citing TNA SP16/7/120-124: Compare, Diana Scarisbrick, 'Anne of Denmark's Jewellery Inventory', ''Archaeologia'', 109 (1991), pp. 208, 214-5.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nFrancis Gofton died in 1628.\n\n==Personal life==\nFrancis Gofton married Katherine Kinsman (d. 1634), the widow of John Pynder (d. 1608), a vintner and Member of Parliament.<ref>[http://www.histparl.ac.uk/volume/1558-1603/member/pynder-john-1608 PYNDER, John (d.1608), of Cheapside, London, ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1558-1603'', ed. P.W. Hasler, 1981.]</ref> In her will, Katherine asked to be buried at the chapel of the [[Worshipful Company of Mercers|Mercers\u2019 Company]] near to John Pynder.<ref>The National Archives, TNA PROB 11/166/65, will of Katherine Gofton.</ref> Their children included:\n* Francis Gofton (d. 1642)\n* John Gofton (1615-1686). His mother left him a house called [[Down Hall, Barrow upon Humber|Downhall in Barrow]], Lincolnshire, and property in Stockwell including farms and the Old Orchard of the manor of Stockwell, with silver plate some formerly belonging to [[Roger Manners, 5th Earl of Rutland]].<ref>The National Archives, TNA PROB 11/166/65.</ref> He was buried at Lambeth.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gofton, Francis}}\n[[Category:1628 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:17th-century English people]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Gofton"}
{"title_page": "John Pudney", "text_new": "{{redirect|Pudney|the New Zealand cricketer|Richard Pudney}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n'''John Sleigh Pudney''' (19 January 1909 \u2013 10 November 1977) was a British poet, journalist and writer.  He was known especially for his popular poetry written during the [[Second World War|Second World War]], but he also wrote novels, short stories and children's fiction (including the Hartwarp books). Pudney also wrote broad-ranging non-fiction, often commissioned, which served as his primary source of income. \n\n==Education and Early Career==\nJohn Pudney was born at [[Langley, Berkshire|Langley Marish]], the only son of Henry William Pudney (a farmer and countryman) and Mabel Sleigh Pudney. He was educated at [[Gresham's School]], [[Holt, Norfolk|Holt]], where he first encountered [[W. H. Auden]], [[Benjamin Britten]], and [[Humphrey Spender]]. He left school in 1925 at the age of sixteen, and spent several years working as an estate agent and studying to become a surveyor. However, he began contributing articles to the [[News Chronicle|News Chronicle]] at the same time, also writing short stories and channelling his love of the countryside into verse.<ref name=dnb>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/31573Roger Lubbock, \u2018Pudney, John Sleigh (1909\u20131977)\u2019, rev. Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, May 2006]</ref> At this time he was one of a group of young writers (including [[Dylan Thomas]], [[George Barker (poet)|George Barker]] and [[David Gascoyne]]) who gathered about the well-known bookshop at No 4, Parton Street, near London's [[Red Lion Square]], run by David Archer.<ref>[https://www.penpushermagazine.co.uk/magazine/issues/article/215/ Goodall, Anna. 'Parton Street Bookshop' in ''Pen Pusher'']</ref> His first published collection of verse, ''Spring Encounter'', came out in 1933 from [[Methuen Publishing|Methuen]] and gained the attention of [[Lady Ottoline Morrell]] who became a patron. Pudney also wrote for [[The Listener]], and worked as a producer at the [[BBC]], where he produced the radio play ''Hadrian's Wall'' with text by Auden and music by Britten, which was broadcast from Newcastle on 25 November 1937.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IMFZ8a8aNHUC&pg=PT116&lpg=PT116&dq=John+Pudney+Benjamin+Britten&source=bl&ots=MUhRGApbmp&sig=ACfU3U2b1caNszL8RMuBi3jjBlRlW4z0Lw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi8-c67k8zoAhUJesAKHRsaDzIQ6AEwCXoECAsQOA#v=onepage&q=John%20Pudney%20Benjamin%20Britten&f=false Warden, C. ''British Avant-Garde Theatre'' (2012)]</ref><ref>[https://www.nmcrec.co.uk/roman-wall-blues NMC Music. ''Benjamin Britten, Roman Wall Blues'']</ref> While at the BBC he also wrote one of the first plays for television - ''Edna's Fruit Hat'' - which was broadcast on 27 January 1939.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/c9ebf9521e9540b4bd20fbc5126034c5 ''Radio Times'' Issue 799, 22 January 1939, p 17]</ref> His first novel, ''Jacobson's Ladder'', describing literary and criminal life in 1930s [[Soho]], appeared in 1938.<ref>[https://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/taro/uthrc/00112/00112-P.html John Pudney Papers at the Harry Ransom Research Center]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-GiDDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=John+Pudney+Jacobsons%27+Ladder&source=bl&ots=7jsAyWhnUt&sig=ACfU3U0ODy1oYxRY7bMp-r4kBZAi75sLFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjlxsiGn8zoAhWxolwKHdxmCjYQ6AEwDnoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=John%20Pudney&f=false Cottrell, Anna. ''London Writing of the 1930s'' (2018) p 88]</ref>\n\n==War Poetry==\nIt was the advent of the Second World War that enabled Pudney to find his subject - the effect that war has on the lives of ordinary people - and with it, his audience.<ref name=times>''The Times'' obituary, 11 November 1977, p 17</ref> In 1940 he was commissioned into the [[Royal Air Force]] as an intelligence officer and as a member of the [[Air Ministry]]'s Creative Writers Unit - a non-combatant role. It was while he was serving as squadron intelligence officer at [[RAF St Eval]] in Cornwall that Pudney wrote one of the best-known poems of the war.<ref name=dnb/> ''For Johnny'' evoked popular fellow-feeling in the London of 1941.<ref>[http://www.carolinemdavies.co.uk/2012/06/07/collected-poems-john-pudney/ Davies, Caroline. ''Collected Poems, John Pudney'']</ref> Written during an air raid, it was published first in the ''News Chronicle'', and featured significantly in the film ''[[The Way to the Stars]]'':\n\n<poem>\nDo not despair\nFor Johnny-head-in-air;\nHe sleeps as sound\nAs Johnny underground.\n\nFetch out no shroud\nFor Johnny-in-the-cloud;\nAnd keep your tears\nFor him in after years.\n\nBetter by far\nFor Johnny-the-bright-star,\nTo keep your head,\nAnd see his children fed.\n</poem>\n\nPudney published several collections of poetry during the war which between them sold over a quarter of a million copies.<ref name=white>White, Michael. 'Johnny Head-in-Air', in ''The Guardian'', 6 April, 1972, p 10</ref>\n\n==Later Career==\nIn the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|UK General Election of July 1945]], Pudney stood as the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] candidate for [[Sevenoaks (UK Parliament constituency)|Sevenoaks]], polling 14,947 votes, or 36 per cent.<ref>''The International Who's Who'' (Europa Publications Limited, 1963) p. 857</ref><ref>[http://www.psr.keele.ac.uk/area/uk/ge45/i17.htm UK General Election results July 1945] at keele.ac.uk, accessed 10 January 2009</ref>\n\nAfter the war he continued to write and worked as a journalist and editor. He was the book critic for [[The Daily Express]] from 1945 and with the ''[[News Review]]'' from 1948 to 1950. He then shifted into publishing, as a director and literary adviser to Evans Brothers, Ltd (1950-1953) and Putnam & Co Ltd (1953-1963). In 1953 he wrote the documentary [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0238961/   ''Elizabeth is Queen''] for [[Associated British Picture Corporation|Associated British Path\u00e9]], which received a [[BAFTA]] award. His later poetry, from the collection ''Spill Out'' (1967), took on a more ironic stance, but still vernacular rather than academic, a period reflected in his second Selected Poems collection published in 1973. One of his book blurbs describes him as \"a poet who just missed being an intellectual\".<ref name=white/> Of his novels, ''The Net'' (1952, set in an aeronautical research station) and ''Thin Air'' (1961) were well received.<ref name=times/> [[The Net (1953 film)|''The Net'']] was filmed by director [[Anthony Asquith]] in 1953. His children's books, including the 'Fred and I' series (''Monday Adventure'' etc), and the Hartwarp adventures for younger children, were popular and sold well in the 1950s and 1960s, but haven't remained in print. Between 1949 and 1963 he edited an annual anthology called ''Pick of Today's Short Stories''.\n\n==Private Life==\nOn 30 October 1934 Pudney married Crystal Selwyn Herbert, the daughter of [[A. P. Herbert]], the writer and [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] [[Member of Parliament]]. They had two daughters and a son, but were divorced. In 1955 he married his second wife, Monica Forbes Curtis of the [[Forbes family]]. She helped him recover from his alcoholism, to which he publicly confessed in 1965 and emerged cured in 1967. That process became a subject for his writing. In 1976 he developed cancer of the throat from which he died a year later in much pain. He wrote about his illness unflinchingly in his autobiographical ''Thank Goodness for Cake'', posthumously published in 1978.<ref name=dnb/> His grandson [[Toby Perkins]] is the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Chesterfield]].\n\n==Works==\n\n===Poetry===\n*''Spring Encounter'' (1933)\n*''Open the Sky'' ([[Boriswood]] 1934)\n*''Dispersal Point and other Air Poems'' (1942)\n*''The Grass Grew All Round'' (1942)\n*''Beyond This Disregard'' (1943) poems\n*''South of Forty'' (1943) poems\n*''Ten Summers'': Poems 1933-1943 (1944)\n*''Almanack of Hope'': Sonnets (1944)\n*''Air Force Poetry'' (1944) (anthology, edited with Henry Treese)\n*''Flight above Cloud'' (1944)\n*''World Still There'' (1945)\n*Selected Poems (1946)\n*''Low Life'' (1947)\n*''Commemorations'' (1948)\n*''Sixpenny Songs'' (1953)\n*Collected Poems (1957)\n*''Spill Out'': Poems and Ballads (1967)\n*''Spandrels'': Poems and Ballads (1969)\n*''Take This Orange'': Poems and Ballads (1971)\n*Selected Poems 1967-1973 (1973)\n*''Living in a One-Sided House'' (1976) poems\n*''Writers' Workshop'', poetry anthology publication, editor with [[Norman Hidden]] and [[Michael Johnson (editor)|Michael Johnson]] (from 1967)<ref>Durham University. [http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ark/32150_s17w62f823m.xml Norman Hidden Collection]</ref>\n\n===Novels===\n*''Jacobson's Ladder'' (1938)\n*''Shuffley Wanderers'' (1948)\n*''The Accomplice'' (1950)\n*''Hero of a Summer's Day'' (1951)\n*''The Net'' (1952)\n*''A Ring for Luck'' (1953)\n*''Trespass in the Sun'' (1957)\n*''Thin Air'' (1961)\n*''Tunnel to the Sky'' (1965)\n*''The Long Time Growing Up'' (1971) novel\n\n===Short stories===\n*''And Lastly the Fireworks'' ([[Boriswood]] 1935)\n*''Uncle Arthur and other stories'' (1939)\n*''Edna's Fruit Hat'' (1946)\n*''It Breathed Down My Neck'' (1946)\n*''The Europeans'': Fourteen tales of a Continent (1948)\n*''The Pick of Today's Short Stories'', 14 volumes (1949-1963), anthologies, editor\n*''The Trampoline'' (1959)\n\n===For Children===\n*''Saturday Adventure'' (1950) \"a story for boys\"\n*''Sunday Adventure'' (1951)\n*''Monday Adventure: The Secrets of Blackmead Abbey'' (1952)\n*''Tuesday Adventure'' (1953)\n*''Wednesday Adventure'' (1954)\n*''Thursday Adventure'' (1955)\n*''Friday Adventure'' (1956)\n*''Spring Adventure'' (1961)\n*''Summer Adventure'' (1962)\n*''The Hartwarp Light Railway'' (1962)\n*''The Hartwarp Balloon'' (1963)\n*''The Hartwarp Circus'' (1963)\n*''The Hartwarp Bakehouse'' (1964)\n*''Autumn Adventure'' (1964)\n*''The Hartwarp E''xplosion'' (1965)\n*''Winter Adventure (1965)\n*''The Grandfather Clock'' (1966)\n*''The Hartwarp Jets'' (1967)\n\n===Biography===\n*''Who Only England Know'' (1943)\n*''Home & Away - An Autobiographical Gambit'' (1960)\n*''Thank Goodness for Cake'' (1978)\n\n===Non Fiction===\n* ''Who Only England Know'' (1943)\n* ''The Air Battle of Malta'' (1944) (HMSO Information Books)\n* ''Atlantic Bridge'' (1945) HMSO (Information Books)\n*''Estuary, a Romance'' (1947)\n* ''Music on the South Bank: An Appreciation of The Royal Festival Hall''.(1951)\n*''His Majesty King George VI'' (1952)\n*''The Thomas Cook Story'' (1953)\n*''The Queen's People'' (1953), photographs by [[Izis Bidermanas]]\n*''The Smallest Room'': a Discreet Survey Through the Ages (1954)\n*''The Book of Leisure'' (1957) editor\n*''The Leisure-Hour Companion'' (1959)\n*''The Seven Skies'' (1959), history of BOAC\n*''A Pride of Unicorns'': [[Richard Atcherley|Richard]] and [[David Atcherley]] of the R.A.F. (1960)\n*''Bristol Fashion''. Some Account of the Earlier Days of Bristol Aviation (1960)\n*''The Camel Fighter'' (1964)\n*''The Golden Age of Stea''m (1967)\n*''Flight and Flying'' (1968) editor\n*''Suez: De Lesseps' Canal'' (1968)\n*''A Draught of Contentment''. The Story of the Courage Group.(1971)\n*''Crossing London's River'': the Bridges, Ferries and Tunnels Crossing the Thames Tideway in London (1972) \n*''Brunel and His World'' (1974)\n*''London's Docks'' (1975)\n*''Lewis Carroll and His World'' (1976)\n*''John Wesley and His World'' (1978)\n\n==References==\n*[https://norman.hrc.utexas.edu/fasearch/findingAid.cfm?eadid=00112s Biographical Sketch of John Pudney at the University of Texas]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/person.asp?LinkID=mp18871 John Pudney at the National Portrait Gallery]\n*[http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/pudney_john John Pudney entry in SFE The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction]\n* [https://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/taro/uthrc/00112/00112-P.html John Pudney: An Inventory of His Papers at the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pudney, John}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gresham's School]]\n[[Category:People from Slough]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:20th-century British poets]]\n[[Category:British male poets]]\n[[Category:English children's writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Pudney|the New Zealand cricketer|Richard Pudney}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n'''John Sleigh Pudney''' (19 January 1909 \u2013 10 November 1977) was a British poet, journalist and writer.  He was known especially for his popular poetry written during the [[Second World War|Second World War]], but he also wrote novels, short stories and children's fiction (including the Hartwarp books). Pudney also wrote broad-ranging non-fiction, often commissioned, which served as his primary source of income. \n\n==Education and Early Career==\nJohn Pudney was born at [[Langley, Berkshire|Langley Marish]], the only son of Henry William Pudney (a farmer and countryman) and Mabel Sleigh Pudney. He was educated at [[Gresham's School]], [[Holt, Norfolk|Holt]], where he first encountered [[W. H. Auden]], [[Benjamin Britten]], and [[Humphrey Spender]]. He left school in 1925 at the age of sixteen, and spent several years working as an estate agent and studying to become a surveyor. However, he began contributing articles to the [[News Chronicle|News Chronicle]] at the same time, also writing short stories and channelling his love of the countryside into verse.<ref name=dnb>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/31573Roger Lubbock, \u2018Pudney, John Sleigh (1909\u20131977)\u2019, rev. Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, May 2006]</ref> At this time he was one of a group of young writers (including [[Dylan Thomas]], [[George Barker (poet)|George Barker]] and [[David Gascoyne]]) who gathered about the well-known bookshop at No 4, Parton Street, near London's [[Red Lion Square]], run by David Archer.<ref>[https://www.penpushermagazine.co.uk/magazine/issues/article/215/ Goodall, Anna. 'Parton Street Bookshop' in ''Pen Pusher'']</ref> His first published collection of verse, ''Spring Encounter'', came out in 1933 from [[Methuen Publishing|Methuen]] and gained the attention of [[Lady Ottoline Morrell]] who became a patron. Pudney also wrote for [[The Listener]], and worked as a producer at the [[BBC]], where he produced the radio play ''Hadrian's Wall'' with text by Auden and music by Britten, which was broadcast from Newcastle on 25 November 1937.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IMFZ8a8aNHUC&pg=PT116&lpg=PT116&dq=John+Pudney+Benjamin+Britten&source=bl&ots=MUhRGApbmp&sig=ACfU3U2b1caNszL8RMuBi3jjBlRlW4z0Lw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi8-c67k8zoAhUJesAKHRsaDzIQ6AEwCXoECAsQOA#v=onepage&q=John%20Pudney%20Benjamin%20Britten&f=false Warden, C. ''British Avant-Garde Theatre'' (2012)]</ref><ref>[https://www.nmcrec.co.uk/roman-wall-blues NMC Music. ''Benjamin Britten, Roman Wall Blues'']</ref> While at the BBC he also wrote one of the first plays for television - ''Edna's Fruit Hat'' - which was broadcast on 27 January 1939.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/c9ebf9521e9540b4bd20fbc5126034c5 ''Radio Times'' Issue 799, 22 January 1939, p 17]</ref> His first novel, ''Jacobson's Ladder'', describing literary and criminal life in 1930s [[Soho]], appeared in 1938.<ref>[https://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/taro/uthrc/00112/00112-P.html John Pudney Papers at the Harry Ransom Research Center]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-GiDDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=John+Pudney+Jacobsons%27+Ladder&source=bl&ots=7jsAyWhnUt&sig=ACfU3U0ODy1oYxRY7bMp-r4kBZAi75sLFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjlxsiGn8zoAhWxolwKHdxmCjYQ6AEwDnoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=John%20Pudney&f=false Cottrell, Anna. ''London Writing of the 1930s'' (2018) p 88]</ref>\n\n==War Poetry==\nIt was the advent of the Second World War that enabled Pudney to find his subject - the effect that war has on the lives of ordinary people - and with it, his audience.<ref name=times>''The Times'' obituary, 11 November 1977, p 17</ref> In 1940 he was commissioned into the [[Royal Air Force]] as an intelligence officer and as a member of the [[Air Ministry]]'s Creative Writers Unit - a non-combatant role. It was while he was serving as squadron intelligence officer at [[RAF St Eval]] in Cornwall that Pudney wrote one of the best-known poems of the war.<ref name=dnb/> ''For Johnny'' evoked popular fellow-feeling in the London of 1941.<ref>[http://www.carolinemdavies.co.uk/2012/06/07/collected-poems-john-pudney/ Davies, Caroline. ''Collected Poems, John Pudney'']</ref> Written during an air raid, it was published first in the ''News Chronicle'', and featured significantly in the film ''[[The Way to the Stars]]'':\n\n<poem>\nDo not despair\nFor Johnny-head-in-air;\nHe sleeps as sound\nAs Johnny underground.\n\nFetch out no shroud\nFor Johnny-in-the-cloud;\nAnd keep your tears\nFor him in after years.\n\nBetter by far\nFor Johnny-the-bright-star,\nTo keep your head,\nAnd see his children fed.\n</poem>\n\nPudney published several collections of poetry during the war which between them sold over a quarter of a million copies.<ref name=white>White, Michael. 'Johnny Head-in-Air', in ''The Guardian'', 6 April, 1972, p 10</ref>\n\n==Later Career==\nIn the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|UK General Election of July 1945]], Pudney stood as the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] candidate for [[Sevenoaks (UK Parliament constituency)|Sevenoaks]], polling 14,947 votes, or 36 per cent.<ref>''The International Who's Who'' (Europa Publications Limited, 1963) p. 857</ref><ref>[http://www.psr.keele.ac.uk/area/uk/ge45/i17.htm UK General Election results July 1945] at keele.ac.uk, accessed 10 January 2009</ref>\n\nAfter the war he continued to write and worked as a journalist and editor. He was the book critic for [[The Daily Express]] from 1945 and with the ''[[News Review]]'' from 1948 to 1950. He then shifted into publishing, as a director and literary adviser to Evans Brothers, Ltd (1950-1953) and Putnam & Co Ltd (1953-1963). In 1953 he wrote the documentary [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0238961/   ''Elizabeth is Queen''] for [[Associated British Picture Corporation|Associated British Path\u00e9]], which received a [[BAFTA]] award. His later poetry, from the collection ''Spill Out'' (1967), took on a more ironic stance, but still vernacular rather than academic, a period reflected in his second Selected Poems collection published in 1973. One of his book blurbs describes him as \"a poet who just missed being an intellectual\".<ref name=white/> Of his novels, ''The Net'' (1952, set in an aeronautical research station) and ''Thin Air'' (1961) were well received.<ref name=times/> [[The Net (1953 film)|The Net]] was filmed by director [[Anthony Asquith]] in 1953. His children's books, including the 'Fred and I' series (''Monday Adventure'' etc), and the Hartwarp adventures for younger children, were popular and sold well in the 1950s and 1960s, but haven't remained in print. Between 1949 and 1963 he edited an annual anthology called ''Pick of Today's Short Stories''.\n\n==Private Life==\nOn 30 October 1934 Pudney married Crystal Selwyn Herbert, the daughter of [[A. P. Herbert]], the writer and [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] [[Member of Parliament]]. They had two daughters and a son, but were divorced. In 1955 he married his second wife, Monica Forbes Curtis of the [[Forbes family]]. She helped him recover from his alcoholism, to which he publicly confessed in 1965 and emerged cured in 1967. That process became a subject for his writing. In 1976 he developed cancer of the throat from which he died a year later in much pain. He wrote about his illness unflinchingly in his autobiographical ''Thank Goodness for Cake'', posthumously published in 1978.<ref name=dnb/> His grandson [[Toby Perkins]] is the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Chesterfield]].\n\n==Works==\n\n===Poetry===\n*''Spring Encounter'' (1933)\n*''Open the Sky'' ([[Boriswood]] 1934)\n*''Dispersal Point and other Air Poems'' (1942)\n*''The Grass Grew All Round'' (1942)\n*''Beyond This Disregard'' (1943) poems\n*''South of Forty'' (1943) poems\n*''Ten Summers'': Poems 1933-1943 (1944)\n*''Almanack of Hope'': Sonnets (1944)\n*''Air Force Poetry'' (1944) (anthology, edited with Henry Treese)\n*''Flight above Cloud'' (1944)\n*''World Still There'' (1945)\n*Selected Poems (1946)\n*''Low Life'' (1947)\n*''Commemorations'' (1948)\n*''Sixpenny Songs'' (1953)\n*Collected Poems (1957)\n*''Spill Out'': Poems and Ballads (1967)\n*''Spandrels'': Poems and Ballads (1969)\n*''Take This Orange'': Poems and Ballads (1971)\n*Selected Poems 1967-1973 (1973)\n*''Living in a One-Sided House'' (1976) poems\n*''Writers' Workshop'', poetry anthology publication, editor with [[Norman Hidden]] and [[Michael Johnson (editor)|Michael Johnson]] (from 1967)<ref>Durham University. [http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ark/32150_s17w62f823m.xml Norman Hidden Collection]</ref>\n\n===Novels===\n*''Jacobson's Ladder'' (1938)\n*''Shuffley Wanderers'' (1948)\n*''The Accomplice'' (1950)\n*''Hero of a Summer's Day'' (1951)\n*''The Net'' (1952)\n*''A Ring for Luck'' (1953)\n*''Trespass in the Sun'' (1957)\n*''Thin Air'' (1961)\n*''Tunnel to the Sky'' (1965)\n*''The Long Time Growing Up'' (1971) novel\n\n===Short stories===\n*''And Lastly the Fireworks'' ([[Boriswood]] 1935)\n*''Uncle Arthur and other stories'' (1939)\n*''Edna's Fruit Hat'' (1946)\n*''It Breathed Down My Neck'' (1946)\n*''The Europeans'': Fourteen tales of a Continent (1948)\n*''The Pick of Today's Short Stories'', 14 volumes (1949-1963), anthologies, editor\n*''The Trampoline'' (1959)\n\n===For Children===\n*''Saturday Adventure'' (1950) \"a story for boys\"\n*''Sunday Adventure'' (1951)\n*''Monday Adventure: The Secrets of Blackmead Abbey'' (1952)\n*''Tuesday Adventure'' (1953)\n*''Wednesday Adventure'' (1954)\n*''Thursday Adventure'' (1955)\n*''Friday Adventure'' (1956)\n*''Spring Adventure'' (1961)\n*''Summer Adventure'' (1962)\n*''The Hartwarp Light Railway'' (1962)\n*''The Hartwarp Balloon'' (1963)\n*''The Hartwarp Circus'' (1963)\n*''The Hartwarp Bakehouse'' (1964)\n*''Autumn Adventure'' (1964)\n*''The Hartwarp E''xplosion'' (1965)\n*''Winter Adventure (1965)\n*''The Grandfather Clock'' (1966)\n*''The Hartwarp Jets'' (1967)\n\n===Biography===\n*''Who Only England Know'' (1943)\n*''Home & Away - An Autobiographical Gambit'' (1960)\n*''Thank Goodness for Cake'' (1978)\n\n===Non Fiction===\n* ''Who Only England Know'' (1943)\n* ''The Air Battle of Malta'' (1944) (HMSO Information Books)\n* ''Atlantic Bridge'' (1945) HMSO (Information Books)\n*''Estuary, a Romance'' (1947)\n* ''Music on the South Bank: An Appreciation of The Royal Festival Hall''.(1951)\n*''His Majesty King George VI'' (1952)\n*''The Thomas Cook Story'' (1953)\n*''The Queen's People'' (1953), photographs by [[Izis Bidermanas]]\n*''The Smallest Room'': a Discreet Survey Through the Ages (1954)\n*''The Book of Leisure'' (1957) editor\n*''The Leisure-Hour Companion'' (1959)\n*''The Seven Skies'' (1959), history of BOAC\n*''A Pride of Unicorns'': [[Richard Atcherley|Richard]] and [[David Atcherley]] of the R.A.F. (1960)\n*''Bristol Fashion''. Some Account of the Earlier Days of Bristol Aviation (1960)\n*''The Camel Fighter'' (1964)\n*''The Golden Age of Stea''m (1967)\n*''Flight and Flying'' (1968) editor\n*''Suez: De Lesseps' Canal'' (1968)\n*''A Draught of Contentment''. The Story of the Courage Group.(1971)\n*''Crossing London's River'': the Bridges, Ferries and Tunnels Crossing the Thames Tideway in London (1972) \n*''Brunel and His World'' (1974)\n*''London's Docks'' (1975)\n*''Lewis Carroll and His World'' (1976)\n*''John Wesley and His World'' (1978)\n\n==References==\n*[https://norman.hrc.utexas.edu/fasearch/findingAid.cfm?eadid=00112s Biographical Sketch of John Pudney at the University of Texas]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/person.asp?LinkID=mp18871 John Pudney at the National Portrait Gallery]\n*[http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/pudney_john John Pudney entry in SFE The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction]\n* [https://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/taro/uthrc/00112/00112-P.html John Pudney: An Inventory of His Papers at the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pudney, John}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gresham's School]]\n[[Category:People from Slough]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:20th-century British poets]]\n[[Category:British male poets]]\n[[Category:English children's writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Sfjohna", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater Career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Pudney"}
{"title_page": "Jenny Raven", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{EngvarB|date= January 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| image =\n| caption = \n| name = Jenny Raven \n| birth_date = 2nd Nov - year Unknown<ref name=\"birthday\">{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BprOleRBiXL/?hl=en |title=Jenny Raven birthday |publisher=instagram.com |date=2018 }}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Hong Kong]],\n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 2003 \u2013 present.\n| spouse =\n}}\n\n'''Jenny Raven '''is a Hong Kong-British actress born in [[Hong Kong]], best known for playing Irina Wong in the feature film remake of ''[[Flatliners]]'' and Sasha Dixon in [[Designated survivor|Designated Survivor]]. Another notable performance was in 2017 as Jasmine in ''[[Arkangel (Black Mirror)|Arkangel]],'' a [[List of Black Mirror episodes|Series 4]] episode of ''[[Black Mirror]]'' (TV Series).\n\n==Early Life==\nJenny Raven was born and raised in [[Hong Kong]].<ref name=\"flock\">{{cite web|url=http://www.withoutaflock.com/news/featured-flock-member-jenny-raven-actor |title=Featured Flock Member : Jenny Raven : Actor |publisher=withoutaflock.com |date=2017 }}</ref> and trained in acting and classical [[ballet]]. She moved to [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada and graduated from the [[University of Toronto]] with a Bachelor of Science.<ref name=\"flock\" />\n\n==Career==\nRaven first appeared in the [[Cantonese]] spoken [[Hong Kong]] Film ''[[Men Suddenly in Black]]'' in 2003.<ref name=\"flock\" /> After moving to [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]] and graduating, Raven landed a main role as Margo Dubois in the children's comedy TV series ''[[Majority Rules!]]'' for 26 episodes from 2009 to 2011.<ref name=\"flock\" /> Raven worked alongside [[Juno Temple]] and [[Rhys Ifans]] in the indie drama comedy ''[[Len and Company]]'' which premiered at TIFF 2015.<ref name=\"gorn\">{{cite web|url=https://gornoblonde.wordpress.com/2016/11/05/canadian-vixen-jenny-raven/|title=Canadian Vixen: Jenny Raven|date=2016|publisher=gornoblonde.wordpress.com}}</ref>\n\nRaven appeared in the 2017 remake of [[Flatliners (2017 film)|''Flatliners'']] as Irina Wong. In December 2017, she appeared as Jasmine in ''[[Arkangel (Black Mirror)|Arkangel]]'', an episode of ''[[Black Mirror]]''.<ref name=\"black\">{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/249802702 |title=Jenny Raven in Black Mirror|publisher=vimeo.com|date=2018}}</ref>\n\nRaven played a recurring role as Sasha Dixon in 10 episodes of the TV series [[Designated Survivor (TV series)|Designated Survivor]] from 2017-2018.<ref name=\"dixon\">{{cite web|url=https://vimeopro.com/editplus/insight-entertainment/video/251384716 |title=Jenny Raven - Designated Survivor, Selected Scenes|publisher=vimeopro.com|date=2019}}</ref> Raven has made single-episode appearances in numerous TV shows such as ''[[Private Eyes (TV series)|Private Eyes]]'', ''[[The L.A. Complex]],'' ''[[Good Witch (TV series)|Good Witch]], [[Lost Girl]], and [[Tom Clancy's Jack Ryan]]''<ref name=\"flock\" />. \n\nRaven is due to appear in the Franky Films Horror flick ''Woodland Grey'' which is due to be aired in 2020.<ref name=\"wood\">{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/first-woodland-grey-production-stills-jenny-raven-and-ryan-blakely-at-work-211 |title=First Woodland Grey production stills Jenny Raven and Ryan Blakely at work |publisher=joblo.com|date=2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n|-\n| 2020\n|''Woodland Grey'' <ref name=\"wood\" />\n| Emily\n|-\n| 2019\n|''Lloyd loses everything'' (Short film)\n| Issy\n|-\n| 2019\n|''Goliath''\n| Tiffany\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[Riot Girls]]''\n| Caine\n|-\n| 2017 \n| ''Bree and Drew (Me & You)'' (Short film)\n| Bree\n|-\n| 2017 \n| ''[[Flatliners (2017 film)]]''\n| Irina Wong<ref name=\"gorn\" />\n|-\n| 2017 \n| ''Our Practice'' (Short film) \n| Madison \n|-\n| 2015 \n| ''[[Cold Deck]]'' \n| Nadine<ref name=\"gorn\" />\n|-\n| 2015 \n| ''Let's Rap''