rican]] [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for the [[Mexico women's national football team|Mexico women's national football (soccer) team]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Carr |first=John |url=http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/blog/_/name/five_aside/id/6724883 |title=Previewing Day 6 of Women's World Cup \u2013 soccer \u2013 ESPN |publisher=ESPN  |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[John Pescoran]] (1980\u2013) ('''r'''), artist\n*'''[[Bill Quirk]]''' ('''a'''), California State Assemblyman, former Hayward City Council member\n* [[Romesh Ratnesar]] (1975\u2013) ('''b'''), journalist, author, former deputy managing editor at ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'' magazine,  member of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]]\n* [[Mike Reilly (politician)|Mike Reilly]] (1944\u2013) ('''b'''), [[United States Democratic Party|Democrat]]ic [[Sonoma County, California|Sonoma County]] supervisor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-yearbook.com/yearbooks/Hayward_High_School_Agrarian_Yearbook/1960/Page_165.html |title=Hayward High School \u2013 Agrarian Yearbook (Hayward, CA), Class of 1960, Page 165 |publisher=E-yearbook.com |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Hi-res-rosa-rios.jpg|thumb|150px|right|[[Rosa Gumataotao Rios]]]]\n* [[Faye Resnick|Faye Hutchison Resnick]], O.J. Simpson murder trial figure, crowned the Maid of Hayward 1975<ref>{{cite news|journal=L.A. Times|title='Diary' Opens a New, Lurid Chapter: Author Faye Resnick's bumps in the fast lane would be unremarkable except that she shared some of them with Nicole Simpson|date=October 20, 1994|authors=RALPH FRAMMOLINO and SHAWN HUBLER, ''TIMES'' STAFF WRITERS|page= 2 of 3|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-10-20/local/me-52588_1_nicole-simpson/2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|journal=The Daily Review|page=Cover|date=May 23, 1975|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/daily-review/1975-05-23}}</ref>\n* [[Rosa Gumataotao Rios]] (1965\u2013) ('''r'''), former [[Treasurer of the United States]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionhispanausa.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=543:from-hayward-to-the-white-house&catid=29:historias-locales-empty&Itemid=4 |title=From Hayward to the White House |publisher=Visionhispanausa.com |date=November 29, 2010 |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Maud Russell]] ('''b''') (1893\u20131989), welfare worker, educator, author\n* '''[[Steve Sapontzis]]''', professor emeritus of philosophy at [[California State University, East Bay]]\n* [[France Silva]] (1876\u20131951) ('''b'''), first [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marine]] of [[Mexican-American]] and [[Hispanic-American|Hispanic]] heritage to receive the [[Medal of Honor]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portuguesefoundation.org/silva.html |title=silva |publisher=Portuguesefoundation.org |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Diamon Simpson]] (1987\u2013) ('''r'''), basketball player with the [[Houston Rockets]]\n* [[Henry Snyder]] (1929\u20132016) ('''b'''), professor emeritus of history at the [[University of California, Riverside]] \n* [[Sokei-an]] (1882\u20131945) ('''a'''), Japanese national, founder of the [[Rinzai]] [[Buddhist Society of America]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tricycle.com/ancestors/zen-yawn-a-cat-sokei-shigetsu-sasaki |title=Zen in the Yawn of a Cat: Sokei-an Shigetsu Sasaki |publisher=Tricycle |date=December 7, 1941 |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Spice 1]] (1970\u2013) ('''r'''), rap musician, active 1991 to present<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/12/07/BAMJTPN3S.DTL |title=HAYWARD / Rapper Spice 1 shot, recovering in hospital |work=San Francisco Chronicle  |date=December 7, 2007 |accessdate=November 13, 2011 |first=Henry K. |last=Lee}}</ref>\n* [[Shawn Stasiak]] (1970\u2013) ('''b'''), professional wrestler, [[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation / Entertainment]] [[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|fifteen time]] [[WWE Hardcore Championship|Hardcore Champion]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shawnstasiak.com/acting-film/ |title=Shawn Stasiak Acting And Film &#124; The Official Home Of Shawn Stasiak |publisher=Shawnstasiak.com |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Bob Sweikert]] (1926\u20131956) ('''r'''), racing driver, [[Indianapolis 500]] winner\n* [[Erick Threets]] (1981\u2013) ('''r'''), Major League Baseball pitcher<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=threeer01 |title=Erick Threets Baseball Stats by Baseball Almanac |publisher=Baseball-almanac.com |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Don Wakamatsu]] (1963\u2013) ('''r'''), Major League Baseball player and manager<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3712791 |title=Seattle Mariners hire Don Wakamatsu as manager |publisher=ESPN |date=November 20, 2008 |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Kristi Yamaguchi at Heart Truth 2009.jpg|thumb|150px|right|[[Kristi Yamaguchi]]]]\n* [[Bill Walsh (American football coach)|Bill Walsh]] (1931\u20132007) ('''r'''), NFL Hall of Fame coach<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/football-coach-bill-walsh-is-born |title=Football coach Bill Walsh is born \u2013 History.com This Day in History \u2013 November 30, 1931 |publisher=History.com |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Andre Ward]] (1984\u2013) ('''r'''), boxer, [[light heavyweight]] gold medalist in the [[2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Olympics]], and current [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] World Super Middleweight champion<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesportscourier.com/content/andre-ward-remembers-father-who-inspired-him |title=Andre Ward remembers the father who inspired him |publisher=TheSportsCourier.com |date=November 30, 2010 |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Joan Weston]] (1935\u20131997) ('''a'''), A.K.A. the \"Blonde Bomber\", famous personality in the original [[roller derby]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Lee |first=Jean H. |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970713&slug=2549244 |title=Sports &#124; Roller Derby Star Was Fierce Competitor &#124; Seattle Times Newspaper |publisher=Community.seattletimes.nwsource.com |date=July 13, 1997 |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[The Dixie Bee-Liners|Buddy Woodward]] (1963\u2013) ('''r'''), musician, composer, singer, actor and [[anime]] voice performer; member of [[The Dixie Bee-Liners]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daddario.com/DaddarioArtistDetails.Page?ActiveID=2049&ArtistId=45301&ArtistName=Buddy_Woodward&sid=0ad0dcaa-3836-4f34-aec4-27d1536e4f21  |title=Buddy Woodward|publisher=Daddario.com |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Kristi Yamaguchi]] (1971\u2013) ('''b'''), professional figure skater, Olympic gold medalist and inductee into the [[U.S. Olympic Hall of Fame]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/sports/exhibit/firsts/yamaguchi/index.cfm |title=Sports: Breaking Records, Breaking Barriers &#124; Kristi Yamaguchi &#124; Smithsonian's National Museum of American History &#124; |publisher=Americanhistory.si.edu |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n*[[Mike Young (baseball)|Mike Young]] (1960\u2013) ('''r'''), professional baseball player<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/y/youngmi01.shtml |title = Mike Young Stats}}</ref>\n* [[Hamza Yusuf]] (1958\u2013) ('''a'''), American convert to Islam, [[Ulama|Islamic scholar]], co-founder of [[Zaytuna College]] originally located in Hayward, now in [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Goodstein |first=Laurie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/19/us/nation-challenged-american-muslims-influential-american-muslims-temper-their.html |title=A NATION CHALLENGED \u2013 THE AMERICAN MUSLIMS \u2013 A NATION CHALLENGED \u2013 THE AMERICAN MUSLIMS \u2013 Influential American Muslims Temper Their Tone |work=The New York Times |date=October 19, 2001 |accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Goto Zuigan]] (1879\u20131965) ('''a'''), Japanese Rinzai Buddhist, operated a strawberry far